<HEADLINE> Music Sales Growth Forecast in Latin America </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The music industry is poised for
dramatic sales growth in Latin American and Eastern European
countries over the next decade, according to report of a market
research company.
</P>
<P>
The report, compiled by the Market Tracking International, said
that the music sales are expected to increase by 167 percent in
Latin America and by 322 percent in Eastern Europe by 2005.
</P>
<P>
Asia has been one of the music industry's most fertile new
music markets of the 1990s, reflecting the region's buoyancy and
reforms of inward investment controls, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report predicted that Latin America and Eastern
Europe are set to show equally aggressive growth over the next few
years, as economic conditions improve and record companies step up
efforts to curb piracy.
</P>
<P>
Music sales rose sharply in Latin America last year
particularly in Brazil, where some 1.39 billion dollars worth of
recordings were sold, 33 percent up on the previous year, the
report said. Some 483 million albums with a retail value of 6.7
billion U.S. dollars would be sold in the region during 2005.
</P>
<P>
Eastern Europe, which is set for even stronger growth, will see
349 million albums with a retail value of 2.7 billion dollars sold
in 2005.
</P>
<P>
The report expected particularly aggressive growth in the
Balkan and former Soviet republics, with Russia tipped to become
Eastern Europe's largest market, selling 1.4 billion dollars worth
of recordings in 2005. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
