<HEADLINE> East Asia, Pacific to Lead World in Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The East Asia and Pacific region is
set to become the world's biggest regional supplier of travelers,
according to a report of the World Tourism Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The number of trips taken by people living in the East Asia and
Pacific region outstripped those taken by North America for the
first time last year, the WTO report said.
</P>
<P>
Travel from East Asia and the Pacific grew by 8 percent, much
higher than from any other part of the world, to 94 million trips
last year, the report said. North Americans made 92 million trips
abroad over the same period.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the emerging economies of China, South
Korea, Malaysia, the Philippines and Singapore are producing most
of the region's new international travelers.
</P>
<P>
"More than 5 million Chinese traveled abroad in 1996; their
strong desire to travel, coupled with steady economic growth,
could soon make China the dominant player in the region's
tourism," a WTO official said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, travel to East Asia and the Pacific grew by 9.3
percent to 87 million visits last year, but the report warned that
the region's tourism could be held back by airport congestion.
</P>
<P>
Earnings from international tourism increased by 9.8 percent to
81 billion U.S. dollars, the report said. Receipts from Hong Kong
and China's inland areas totaled 21 billion dollars last year,
making it the fifth biggest tourism earner after the United States,
Spain, France and Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
