<HEADLINE> Quebec to Seek More French-Speaking Immigrants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Quebec government is planning
to increase the number of French-speaking immigrants to the
province, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
The government has proposed increasing the number of
independent immigrants from 82,169 in 1995-97 to a maximum of
93,400 over the next three years and making knowledge of French a
major criterion.
</P>
<P>
During the 1995-97 period, the Quebec provincial government
selected only one of every two immigrants, while the other was
chosen by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
In the 1998-2000 period, Quebec will use an immigration
agreement with the federal government to select 57 percent of the
total number of immigrants and make knowledge of French an even
more important selection criteria.
</P>
<P>
"We want to be able to see these people integrate to the Quebec
society and participate and work and give, as they want to do, to
the Quebec society," Andre Boisclair, Quebec's minister of
immigration, was quoted by the Globe and Mail newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that only 13 percent of immigrants to Canada
choose to live in Quebec, which has less than a quarter of the
Canadian population.
</P>
<P>
The province complained that the federal government is slow to
clarify the status of refugees in the province and the federal
tariffs on immigrants cost twice as much for an immigrant to come
to Quebec than to provinces without control of immigrant
selection.
</P>
<P>
It denied the suggestion that immigrants turn down Quebec
because of the debate over the province's political future.
</P>
<P>
According to a recent government survey, 52 percent of
respondents supported maintaining the current level of immigrants
to Quebec, while 10 percent supported increasing the number.
</P>
</TEXT>
