<HEADLINE> Canada Develops New Technique to Keep Donor Hearts Fit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A simple treatment developed at
Canada's Toronto Hospital more than doubles the time a donor heart
can be kept healthy before transplant, said a report today.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Christopher Feindel, surgical director of the hospital's
heart-transplant program, has found that keeping blood coursing
through the heart protects its cells for up to eight hours.
</P>
<P>
This will make it possible to transport a donor heart over a
long distance and will make transplants easier and safer.
</P>
<P>
The current practice is for a heart removed from a donor to be
placed on ice for transport. While cooling slows the deterioration
of cells, within four hours, the organ is no longer usable for
transplant.
</P>
<P>
The new technique is a variation of a procedure known as
perfusion. Three liters of blood taken from the body of the donor
during removal of the heart are filtered to remove any clots and
are placed in blood bags.
</P>
<P>
From there, the blood is then slowly run back into the heart
through a small tube during transport. Only plastic bags and
standard blood transfusion equipment are required.
</P>
<P>
"This is an extremely simple idea. It hasn't been done before
because people always looked at complicated technology," Dr.
Feindel was quoted by the Globe and Mail newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
"I came up with the idea by asking: `Why not eliminate the
equipment and just use the blood that would otherwise be lost from
the donor? Any hospital has the facilities to do it," he said.
</P>
<P>
He has tested the technique on animal heart in the laboratory,
and results showed transplanted hearts had better recovery with
the transfusion technique than they did with the standard method.
</P>
<P>
The finding was reported today in the Journal of Heart and Lung
Transportation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
