<HEADLINE> Convention Urges to Protect Bears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The parties to the ongoing 10th
Conference of the Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species (CITES) in Harare urged to protect bears.
</P>
<P>
The CITES conference drafted a resolution saying that
immediate action should be taken to ''demonstrably'' reduce
illegal trade in bear parts and derivatives to avoid possible
extinction.
</P>
<P>
Noting that long-term solution to conserve bears required
substantive and measurable actions, the conference said this
should be done before the next biennial meeting.
</P>
<P>
Failure to do so could result in extinction of certain bear
populations or species, says the draft resolution made available
during the 12-day conference, which began on June 9.
</P>
<P>
The bear could be saved from extinction by improving national
legislation to control imports and exports of bear parts and products
through harsh penalties to deter illegal trade.
</P>
<P>
The draft resolution also called for ''new national efforts'' in
key producer and consumer countries to identify and eliminate illegal
markets notwithstanding the need to exchange techniques and
intelligence. enditem

