<HEADLINE> South Africa Fails to Re-open Rhino Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- South Africa today narrowly lost its
bid to lift restrictions on trade in rhino horn and other derivatives
of the southern white rhino.
</P>
<P>
The proposal put forward by South Africa to the ongoing 10th
conference of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered
Species (CITES) in Harare was for the amendment of annotation 503 to
allow commercial trade in rhino horn subject to imposition of a zero
export quota between 1997 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
Voting was done by show of hands with South Africa getting 60
votes in its favour and 32 against, narrowly missing the
required two-third majority.
</P>
<P>
The CITES deliberations have been delayed because of lengthy
interventions by parties on such controversial issues as the
elephant, the whale and the rhino.
</P>
<P>
It was the contention of those who opposed South Africa's
proposal that reopening trade in rhino horn even without export
quotas would send the wrong message to illegal traders.
</P>
<P>
India said most rhino horn consuming countries, which used the
horn in traditional medicines, were making progress in finding
alternatives to the product and these efforts would be derailed if
trade was reopened. enditem

=06181631

=06181445
NNNN
00:37 00:37 g # PAB
</P>
