<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Global Environment Initiative Announced in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Brazil, Singapore, South Africa
and Germany announced today their intention to launch a joint
initiative aimed at contributing to worldwide protection of the
natural sources of life and sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The intention was expressed in identical statements issued by
Brazilian President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, Singapore Prime
Minister Goh Chok Tong, First Deputy President of South Africa
Thabo M Mbeki and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
The leaders said they are going to launch the joint initiative
at a special session of the U.N. General Assembly to be held in
New York from June 23 to 27.
</P>
<P>
Five years after the U.N. Conference on Environment and
Development in Rio de Janeiro, the United Nations will be taking
stock of the progress made hitherto and determining the future
focuses of international cooperation in this field at the special
session, they said.
</P>
<P>
"The main objective of the joint initiative mounted by the four
heads of state and government is to achieve concrete progress in
key issues concerning international environment and development
cooperation," they stressed.
</P>
<P>
They said the focus of their initiative will be on measures
aimed at protecting the climate and the forests and on problems of
urban development and questions of anchoring global environmental
protection institutionally to a greater degree within the United
Nations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
