<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Prime Minister Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin
Erbakan announced here today that he had submitted his
resignation to President Suleyman Demirel and would hand over power
to his junior partner center-right True Path Party (DYP)
Chairwoman Tansu Ciller.
</P>
<P>
Following two and a half hours of talks today with Ciller and
Grand Unity Party (BBP) leader Mushin Yazicioglu, Erbakan told
reporters that he had agreed to step down as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
He said that his Islamic Welfare Party (RP), DYP and BBP now
hold a majority in the parliament and a new coalition government
would be formed with the support of BBP.
</P>
<P>
On his part, BBP leader Yazicioglu said it is possible that the
DYP and RP will form a new coalition government, adding that his
party will support the new government from outside.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan, also the Welfare Party leader, believed that Ciller
will head the new government in cooperation with the Islamists and
get a vote of confidence in the parliament.
</P>
<P>
However, skeptics said this is impossible and the military will
never allow the RP to be in the government and Ciller to be the
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Ciller, who is deputy prime minister and foreign minister, has
said that she will ask the president to assign her with the task
of forming a new government, which she will lead until early
elections, whose date is still unknown.
</P>
<P>
Four DYP ministers resigned in less than two months to
pressure Ciller to end the alliance with Erbakan.
</P>
<P>
The RP and DYP formed the coalition government in June, 1996
and signed a power-sharing protocol which stipulated that Erbakan
would head the government for the first two years and then turn it
over to Ciller for the remaining two years.
</P>
<P>
After one year in power, the government faced growing
impatience with Erbakan's inclination to inch the country toward
an Islamic entity and his reluctance to curb the fundamentalist
force in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The military and opposition regarded Erbakan's policies as a
most dangerous threat to Turkey's secularism enshrined in its
constitution.
</P>
<P>
Early this month, Ciller and her party issued an ultimatum to
Erbakan, asking him to hand out power before June 18 or to face a
collapse of the coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Following several rounds of talks, both Erbakan and Ciller said
that a new RP-DYP coalition will be formed with the help of the
(BBP), which has eight deputies in the parliament, and will
definitely obtain a vote of confidence to govern. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
