<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Holds Meeting on Land-Locked, Transit Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A meeting of land-locked
and transit developing countries and their development partners
began here today.
</P>
<P>
In preparation for the three-day meeting, the United Nations
Conference on Trade and Development (UNCTAD) had prepared an
issues paper as well as a series of background documents which
highlight specific progress at the regional, subregional and
international levels towards improvements of transit transport
efficiency. A number of international institutions had also
prepared background documents outlining their activities on half
of the land-locked and transit developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The UNCTAD reported that though a number of improvements have
been made in recent years, transit costs for land-locked
developing countries remain far higher in most cases than those
facing coastal countries, and higher still when compared with the
similar costs facing developed countries. For example, land-locked
countries have a freight-to-import ratio of 17.4 percent, compared
to 8.1 percent for other countries in Africa.
</P>
<P>
At its 50th session in 1995, the General Assembly, as part of
the preparations for the present meeting, called for subregional
consultative meetings between land-locked and transit developing
countries to agree on priority areas for future action.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the UNCTAD and the United Nations Development
Program, the first of such meetings concerning the northeast Asian
subregion was held in Ulan Bator, Mongolia, on May 22 this year.
</P>
<P>
The outcome of the Ulan Bator meeting was a Memorandum of
Understanding between China, Mongolia and the Russian Federation,
which outlines proposals for a future program of action to improve
transit transport arrangements in the subregion. The memorandum
constituted a major breakthrough in cooperative arrangements
between those countries, the UNCTAD reported.
</P>
<P>
There are 29 land-locked developing countries and 27 transit
developing countries. In addition, two developed countries, South
Africa and the Russian Federation, serve as transit neighbors to
land-locked developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
