<HEADLINE> US Considers Mix of Nuclear Warhead Deployment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. government is
considering altering the mix of nuclear warheads on submarines,
bombers and missiles to lower the cost of the arsenal, the
Washington Post reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted senior U.S. officials as saying that one
option under review by the Joint Chiefs of Staff would cut the
number of deployed high-cost ballistic missile submarines and
increase the number of warheads based on cheaper but more
vulnerable land-based missiles and strategic bombers.
</P>
<P>
If the plan was implemented, the cost of maintaining a total
strategic stockpile of more than 10,000 nuclear warheads, of which
6,000 are currently deployed, would be cut by some 10 billion U.S.
dollars between 1998 and 2003.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. government wants to maintain the present size of the
nuclear arsenal to keep pressure on the Russian legislature for
ratification of the 1993 START II treaty, which sets a ceiling of
3,500 nuclear warheads. But it hopes to reduce the cost. 
</P>
</TEXT>
