<HEADLINE> Illegal Ivory Trade Still Rampant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Ivory is still traded on black
market internally despite a 1989 ban on international trade in
the elephant product, animal rights organisation traffic said
here today.
</P>
<P>
It said the Convention on International Trade in Endangered
Species (CITES) provides a very weak institutional mechanism to aid
the vital task of assessing the continuing illicit ivory trade.
</P>
<P>
To fill the information void, however, traffic had developed the
Bad Ivory Database System (BIDS). Preliminary BIDS investigations
had now revealed that the scale of illegal trade in ivory was cause
for concern.
</P>
<P>
It said, "seizures of ivory are ongoing and widespread,
especially in Africa, Europe and United States and parts of Asia.''
</P>
<P>
In September 1996, at least 69 tonnes of ivory and ivory
products had been confiscated worldwide since 1989, said traffic,
adding, "with recent additions to the database, the figure is now
closer to 100 tonnes.''
</P>
<P>
Of the 73 cases of major ivory seizures recorded for which final
destinations could be determined, 80 percent of the ivory was being
exported to Asian markets. Another 14 percent was seized
in Europe without a declared onward destination, with nearly half of
the volume originating in former Zaire and being exported to Spain, a
non-ivory consumer, it said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., India and Ivory Cost accounted for the remaining six
percent of the ivory seized, it said.
</P>
<P>
Traffic said the smuggling techniques included painting ivory
blocks black or brown to resemble wood.
</P>
<P>
Traffic urged tightening of the bad ivory data collection system,
and was now seeking the assistance of the cites secretariat and the
parties themselves to improve data collection. enditem

=06181756

=06181611
