<HEADLINE> U.S, Bolivia Fail to List Mahogany as Endangered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. and Bolivia today lost their
bid to enforce control on trade in the big-leafed mahogany species
at the ongoing conference of Convention on International Trade in
Endangered Species (CITES).
</P>
<P>
The two countries failed to get the required two thirds
majority in secret ballot, with 67 votes in their favor and 45
against them.
</P>
<P>
Presenting its proposal, Bolivia said listing the big-leafed
mahogany under appendix ii would make it possible for producer and
consumer countries to come up with conservation methods that would
ensure its survival.
</P>
<P>
The U.S., which is the largest consumer of big-leafed mahogany
timber, said while a number of the species' range states were engaged
in conservation programs, there was still need to list the species
in order to encourage these efforts.
</P>
<P>
However, countries like Malaysia, Brazil and Cameroon who made
interventions against the proposal said the international convention
was in danger of losing its relevance by resorting to listing all
species in fear of extinction. enditem

=06181759

