<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN: Sustainable Goods, Services Mean Opportunities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- A UN report launched here
today shows that there are real economic, social and environmental
benefits for developing country producers who target their
increasing demand for more sustainable produced goods and
services.
</P>
<P>
Titled Unlocking Trade Opportunities, the report was prepared
by the International Institute for Environment and Development for
the UN Department of Policy Co-ordination and Sustainable
Development.
</P>
<P>
The report presented 10 case studies where developing country
producers have gained export success from worldwide move towards
more sustainable consumption and production patterns.
</P>
<P>
Among the case studies, Century Textiles in India, which moved
quickly to phase out hazardous dyes, won a 10-15 percent price
premium and a growth in sales of 15 in the first year; Fridge
Master in Swaziland became Africa's first fridge maker to phase
out ozone depleting CFCs and increased sales threefold in South
Africa; and tourism initiatives in Jamaica and Senegal profile new
approaches that contribute community and environmental benefits.
</P>
<P>
Development assistance agencies, non-governmental organizations
and business customers of developing country producers can play
crucial roles in supporting their transition to production of more
sustainable goods and services by providing financial and
technical support to build their capacity, assisting in the
certification process, offering credit facilities and developing
long-term relationships with producers, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Governments could greatly increase the potential for increased
export of environmentally and socially preferable products by
eliminating regulations, subsidies and trade barriers which
currently hinder market access, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Development of clear guidelines for transparency, consultation
and phasing in of proposed environmental regulations by developed
country governments would greatly assist developing country
exporters, the report stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
