<HEADLINE> Suspect in CIA Attack Held Without Bond </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The suspect in the 1993
terrorist attack outside CIA headquarters, Mir Aimal Kansi, has
been ordered held without bond at an arraignment in Fairfax County
court, some 40 kilometers west of Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
Kansi, a Pakistani native who was captured and returned to the
United States Tuesday night, was arraigned on two counts of
capital murder, three counts of maiming, and five counts of using
a firearm in the commission of a felony.
</P>
<P>
If convicted, Kansi could be sentenced to death. He was accused
of killing two CIA employees and wounding three other people in
the 1993 assault-rifle attack. A hearing was scheduled on June 27.
</P>
<P>
Circuit Judge J. Howe Brown asked Kansi to verify his identity,
and whether he had a lawyer to represent him. The suspect said
"No," and when Brown asked him why, Kansi patted his pockets and
said he had no money.
</P>
<P>
The 33-year-old Kansi was reportedly captured by several
Afghans near the border between Pakistan and Afghanistan and was
taken to U.S. agents of the Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)
and the Central Intelligence Agency (CIA).
</P>
<P>
He was flown to the United States under extraordinary security
on a military aircraft Tuesday night and was put into the Fairfax
County jail soon after arrival. 
</P>
