<HEADLINE> Iran to Turn Border Area into Free Trade Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Iranian authorities announced here
today that they want to turn the Sarakhs special trade area
bordering Turkmenistan into a free trade zone.
</P>
<P>
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported that the announcement
was made by the High Council for Free Trade and Industrial Zones
headed by President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said that a proposal in this regard has been presented to
the government and, if approved, Sarakhs will be a welcome
addition to the three existing free trade zones -- Kish Island,
Qeshm Island and Chabahar.
</P>
<P>
The three free trade zones are all situated off the southern
coast of the country near the strategically important strait of
Hormuz.
</P>
<P>
IRNA said the council also decided to declare other four areas
as special economic zones -- the Imam Khomeini industrial complex
at the port of the same name on the Persian Gulf, the Amir-Abad
port on the Caspian Sea, Jolfa in East Azarbaijan province near
the Armenian border, and the area which contains the historic
Ark-e-Bam Citadel in Kerman province, southeastern Iran.
</P>
<P>
The declaration of special economic areas is aimed at promoting
investments and non-oil exports, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to accelerate development in the free trade zones, the
Central Bank of Iran (CBI) announced last month that private
interests are allowed to partner up with the public sector to set
up banks there.
</P>
<P>
CBI Governor Mohsen Nourbakhsh said "Foreign banks are also
allowed to open branches at the free trade zones and the domestic
banks are entitled to perform external operations there."
</P>
<P>
Iran has formulated a series of regulations and rules regarding
investment, customs, import and export business, monetary and
banking operations, and utilization of land and natural resources.
</P>
<P>
Despite strenuous efforts by the government, including its
pledge to guarantee security of foreign investments, Iran has made
little progress in luring capital from abroad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
