<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Turkish Premier Resigns But Political dilemma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Prime Minister Necmettin
Erbakan's resignation today put an end to the one-year-old
coalition government but Turkey's political dilemma continues.
</P>
<P>
Following his one-hour meeting with Turkish President Suleyman
Demirel this evening, the Islamic Welfare Party (RP) leader
Erbakan said at a press conference that he had presented his
resignation to Demirel and asked the president to approve the
handover of his post to his partner center-right True Path Party
(DYP) leader Tansu Ciller to form the 55th government.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan made the decision for the resignation after his
three-hour talks with Ciller and Grand Unity Party (BBP) Chairman
Mushin Yazicioglu this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The three party leaders reached an agreement to form a new
government with the premiership of Ciller.
</P>
<P>
Yazicioglu said that his party would support the new coalition
government outside.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the RP parliamentary group meeting Tuesday,
Erbakan said that with the support of the Grand Unity Party
(BBP), his RP and the True Path Party (DYP) would enjoy a
majority in the parliament and could form a new coalition
government.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan said that transferring the premiership to the DYP was a
predetermined issue in the coalition government ptotocol, noting
that an early election would be held as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Erbakan said that the exact date for the early elections
would be announced within the first two weeks of this month
and report would be submitted to the parliament for approval
as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Ciller announced that she would take over
the premiership from Erbakan in the second half of this month,
a year ahead of the schedule set in the power-sharing
protocol.
</P>
<P>
The RP and DYP signed the bipartite protocol in June
1996 which stipulated that Erbakan would head the government for
the first two years and then turn it over to Ciller for
the remaining two years.
</P>
<P>
During one year in power, the coalition saw a growing
impatience with Erbakan's Islamic tendency, regarded by the
military and opposition as a serious threat to Turkey's
secularism enshrined in its Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Analysts here noted that Ciller was forced to take over power
from her coalition partner RP because of the increasing pressure
within her own party.
</P>
<P>
Some DYP parliamentary deputies dissatisfied with Ciller's weak
attitude toward the RP, had threatened to pull out of the party,
posing a direct threat to the RP-DYP parliamentary majority.
</P>
<P>
Repeatedly voicing their grave concern over the expanding
fundamentalism in Turkey, the General Staff of the Turkish
Armed Forces had been exerting pressure on the RP-led coalition
government, causing even military coup rumors in the capital of
Ankara.
</P>
<P>
At a February National Security Council meeting, the generals
led by Chief of General Staff Ismail Hakki Karadayi demanded the
coalition government to take tougher measures against the fast
increasing fundamentalist force in this secular republic but they
were frustrated with the reluctance of Erbakan to curb the
Islamic radicals.
</P>
<P>
The constitution Court is now investigating the anti-secularism
activities of several RP deputies well-known for their Islamic
tendency, increasing the speculation about the closure of the
RP.
</P>
<P>
Although Erbakan was forced to step down under pressure both
from the military and the coalition, political situation still
remains unstable as the military and public opinion are not for
the new coalition government to be formed by the DYP and RP with the
support of the BBP. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Not to Move Embassy to Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today affirmed that it would
not move its Embassy in Israel from Tel Aviv to Jerusalam, a city
in dispute between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Omer Akbel told a regular
news briefing today that Turkey would not move its embassy until
the Middle East Peace Process succeeds and an agreement acceptable
to two sides is in place.
</P>
<P>
Replying a question about the recent U.S. Congress resolution
approving the transfer of the U.S. Embassy to Jerusalem, Akbel
said Turkey's view concerning the city of Jerusalem is well-known,
adding the Turkish embassy is in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
At Monday's press conference, the Foreign Ministry deputy
spokesman Sermet Atacanli failed to comment on the U.S Congress
move, but he said that whatever will be agreed between Israel and
the Palestinians would be acceptable to Turkey as well.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Congress decision on embassy transfer has triggered
strong protests from the Palestinians and other Arab
countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
