<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-18 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Greece Have No Differences on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and Greece have no
differences of views, positions or tactic on Cyprus problem
since there is excellent cooperation between the two governments,
a government spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at his daily press briefing, Government Spokesman
Manolis Christofides said the Greek government will be kept
informed on the course of the forthcoming direct talks between
the Greek and Turkish Cypriot community leaders.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-sponsored face-to-face talks between Glafcos Clerides
and Rauf Denktash will take place on July 9, near New York, to
break the deadlock on the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
Christofides has announced that President Clerides will travel
to Athens on July 2 for talks with the Greek government, prior to
his departure for New York for the direct talks.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also said that the Cypriot government has
decided a moratorium on public statements that might reveal the
Greek Cypriot side's positions and tactics during the forthcoming
U.N.-sponsored direct talks.
</P>
<P>
"In view of the countdown to the start of the direct
talks, we consider it wise not reply to questions which might
lead to a revelation of positions, argumentation or tactics at
the talks," Christofides added.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the session of the National Council, top
political advisory body to the President on handling the Cyprus
issue, scheduled for June 23, Christofides said it is expected
to set out a clear picture of the limits in which the
Greek Cypriot side will move.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unsolved since 1974 when
the island was divided after Turkish troops occupied the
northern third in the wake of a pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
had two informal meetings in Nicosia in October 1994, which
ended in a deadlock. The two men have not met since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
