<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Sceptic About Return to NATO Military Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- French Foreign Minister Hubert
Vedrine said today that he is sceptic about the return of France
to the integrated military structure of NATO in the near future.
</P>
<P>
"I am rather sceptic but I don't want to predict because there
has been really no precise discussion between the president of the
republic and the government on this subject," said Vedrine during
an interview with Radio Info.
</P>
<P>
France has asked the replacement of an American commander by a
European at the Naplese-based NATO Southern Command as a
prediction for its return to the integrated military structure of
the trans-Atlantic military alliance, from which it withdrew in
1966.
</P>
<P>
The United States has rejected the request, citing "vital
interests" for America in the whole Mediterranean area.
</P>
<P>
Vedrine said that it is up to President Jacques Chirac to
decide whether France would return to the integrated military
structure either at the NATO Madrid summit in July or before that,
because it was Chirac who first suggested returning to the
integrated military structure of NATO.
</P>
<P>
"It is for him to decide if he estimates to have received, in
terms of reform of NATO and in terms of the place of France (in
NATO), sufficient elements for France to go along this process or
no," he said.
</P>
<P>
French Defense Minister Alain Richard said last week that the
progress made in the renovation of NATO remains insufficient for
France to immediately return to its integrated military structure.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist Party, which came to power in the legislative
elections, said in its program that it "refuses France's
reintegration into the military structure of NATO" and that "the
security of Europe is above all the affair of Europeans and cannot
be separated from other aspects of the European construction."
</P>
<P>
After becoming president in May 1995, President Chirac launched
the process of a full return by France to NATO, in which it now
only retains a simple membership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Cabinet Approves Pension Reform Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The German government today approved
a plan to overhaul the country's pension system in a bid to
prevent it from plunging into a deep funding crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the reform plan, which still needs parliament approval,
the government wants to gradually cut the pension of an average
wage-earner from the present 70 percent of the net income in his
final working years to 64 percent by the year 2030.
</P>
<P>
The move is intended to stem the rise in pension contributions
and help bridge the widening gap between what is paid into the
nation's state-run pension system and what is being drawn out.
</P>
<P>
Under Germany's current system, pension contributions paid by
an employee are not put aside for his own use in the future, but
are used to pay the needs of those now retiring.
</P>
<P>
Like other Western countries, Germany has increasingly found
that its generous pension scheme is being squeezed by falling
birth rates and consequently the declining labor force on the one
hand and an aging population that is extending its claim on
pension benefits on the other hand.
</P>
<P>
According to German media reports, every pensioner in Germany
is currently paid for by 2.2 employers. This ratio is expected to
fall to 1.6 by the year 2030.
</P>
<P>
German Labor Minister Norbert Bluem, architect of the
government pension reform plan, warned recently that without a
resolution of the country's present pension problems, there could
be a feud between generations.
</P>
<P>
However, before carrying out the much-needed reform, the
government will have to strike a compromise with the main
opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) which has strongly
rejected cuts in pension benefits, arguing that it will turn a
large number of pensioners into social welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
The government needs the support of the SPD for it controls a
majority in the Bundestag, the upper house of parliament. The
first parliament reading of the government plan is scheduled for
next week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
