<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coffee Share in Uganda's Exports to Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Coffee share in Uganda's exports
will fall below 50 percent level by the year 2002, reported the
local daily "The New Vision" today.
</P>
<P>
An International Financing Review report was quoted as saying
that in 1996, coffee accounted for 65 percent of Uganda's 528
million U.S. Dollars export bill while in 1988 when the country
started to diversify the economy as part of a broad economic
reform package, the coffee share in the country's exports was 95
percent.
</P>
<P>
This growing trend, the report said, is due to the
diversification away from coffee production to "fishing, cotton
growing and more sophisticated agricultural products such as
roses, vanilla and spice crops".
</P>
<P>
Coffee has been biggest foreign exchange earner in Uganda's
economy. It is reported that Uganda which exported 4.2 million
bags (60 kilos per bag) in 1995/96 season was the largest coffee
exporter in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
