<HEADLINE> House Panel Upholds China MFN status </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The House Ways and Means
Committee today voted 34 to 5 to uphold President Bill Clinton's
decision to maintain normal U.S. trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
The committee urged members of the full House of
Representatives to reject a resolution that would revoke China's
Most Favored Nation (MFN) trade status.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of maintaining normal trade relations with China
argued it would be counterproductive for the United States to
unilaterally withdraw MFN for China.
</P>
<P>
They said it would be better to shift the debate over relations
with China away from commercial ties and toward issues of concern
like human rights and religion.
</P>
<P>
They believed there was no real value to debate every year on
China's trade status with the United States.
</P>
<P>
Those opposed to extend MFN to China argued they did so because
they put American values ahead of commerce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
