<HEADLINE> Tehran Warns to Shut Off Water to Rich </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- In a move mainly targeted at
the rich, Tehran authorities today announced that starting June
22, they will shut off the water supply to families who use more
than 750 liters of water per person per day.
</P>
<P>
The Persian evening paper Ettela'at reported that the provincial
committee on water crisis has identified those who use too
much water.
</P>
<P>
"These people will first be warned in written forms and then
their water will be shut off if they do not comply," Mohsen
Nariman, Director General of Tehran Province Water and Sewage,
was quoted by the paper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Experts here believe that the water-shut-off program targets
the rich and well-off people, mostly residing in northern
Tehran, who use drinking water for watering their large gardens
and filling their swimming pools.
</P>
<P>
Iran's capital of Tehran has a population of 10 million
and they are supplied with water from two reservoirs -- one
in the northwest and the other in northeast. The water level
is low this year.
</P>
<P>
"The water shortage is serious this year. We ask the
people to reduce their water consumption before we have to cut
off their water," the official said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the consumption limit for each family is
50 cubic meters and the investigation has shown that a
number of families are using twice as much as this amount.
</P>
<P>
The official called on people to report those who use too
much water to the Public Relations Office of the Organization
of Water and Sewage.
</P>
<P>
Tehran's water reserves are dangerously low this year because
of the less rainfall and snow last autumn and winter. The
authorities have been warning the people by showing short
films on Iranian TV and by publishing warnings in the papers.
</P>
<P>
The Water Crisis Committee has also been formed to prevent,
or deal with, problems arising from water shortage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
