<HEADLINE> Extension of US GSP to Tanzania Not Yet Approved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The Ministry of Industries
and Trade of Tanzania today said that the US Congress was yet to
approve the extension of the US Generalized System of Preference
(GSP) to Tanzania, which expired on May 31 this year.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the ministry here said Tanzanian
exporters would have to pay duties on their merchandise upon
entry or release in the United States until the congress
reauthorized the GSP extension.
</P>
<P>
Initially, according to the statement, Tanzania exporters were
benefiting from the facility in terms of preferential or zero
duty entry.
</P>
<P>
GSP is a preferential arrangement through which products of
export from preference benefit countries enter the markets of
preference giving countries at benefits beyond most favored
nation (MFN) status.
</P>
<P>
The ministry did not give the reason, but advised Tanzanian
exporters to state on their commercial invoice that their
products originated from a GSP entitled country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
