<HEADLINE> ECOMOG Warns of Planned Killing of Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- The west African peacekeeping force
known as ECOMOG has warned against planned killing of political
rivals by some ill-willed individuals prior to Liberia's historic
polls next month.
</P>
<P>
The News Agency of Nigeria today quotes ECOMOG force
commander, Major-General Victor Malu, as saying: "ECOMOG
intelligence forces have identified these individuals, and are
closely monitoring them."
</P>
<P>
Malu, however, declined to provide the names or details of the
plots.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to state categorically that in the event of any such
elimination attempt, ECOMOG will hit the individuals involved so
hard that they will be completely crushed," he said.
</P>
<P>
Malu's warning came in the wake of numerous press reports
alleging former warlord and presidential candidate Charles Taylor
has hired and brought into Liberia mercenaries from South
Africa's Inkatha Movement to eliminate opponents during the
campaign period which kicked off in the capital Monrovia on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Taylor and his supporters have denied the allegations.
</P>
<P>
In another development, Malu urged Liberian political
aspirants to avoid the use of "vexing" issues during their
political campaign as they could further re-open the wounds of
the civil war.
</P>
<P>
"I wish to advise political aspirants to concentrate their
campaign talks, discussions and efforts on issues and specific
plans and programs they have to bring improvement to the lives of
the Liberian citizens who have been most tormented by the
disturbances," he said in a broadcast on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The force commander reiterated that ECOMOG will provide
adequate security to all the parties and their aspirants at all
campaign venues and that threats to peace in any part of the
country will be decisively neutralized.
</P>
<P>
Scheduled for July 19, the presidential and legislative polls
are set to crown a peace process outlined in a revised accord
signed last August to end the seven-year civil war ignited by
Taylor in December 1989.
</P>
<P>
Some 200,000 people died in the war while more others were
left homeless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
