<HEADLINE> German FM Hails EU Summit Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
today hailed the deals on European Union (EU)'s single currency
and the bloc's eastward expansion reached at the two-day European
Union (EU) summit in Amsterdam, the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Kinkel said that EU leaders at the meeting had
cleared the way for the EU to expand to eastern Europe by agreeing
to start negotiations on taking in new members at the beginning of
1998.
</P>
<P>
He said this agreement confirmed that the EU would not lose its
capability to act even with 20 or more members.
</P>
<P>
He said the message from Amsterdam, including a budget
stability pact, assured that the planned single currency, Euro,
will be launched punctually on January 1, 1999 with adherence to
the qualification criteria, and that Euro would remain stable in
the long run.
</P>
<P>
The treaty of Amsterdam marked the start of a great European
project comparable with the past milestones of the EU, including
the 1957 Treaty of Rome, the creation of the single European
market in 1992 and the Maastricht treaty on the creation of a
Economic and Monetary Union, Kinkel said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
