<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Trade Deficit Shoots Up by 7.8 Percent in April </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. foreign trade deficit
climbed up by 7.8 percent in April after dropping to a four-month
low in March by record exports, according to a report from the
Commerce Department here today.
</P>
<P>
The department said the deficit in goods and services totaled
8.4 billion U.S. dollars, mainly due to the record high imports
for such consumer goods as clothing, toys and pharmaceutical
products. The monthly figure is up from a revised 7.8 billion
dollars in March. The March imbalance, initially estimated at 8.5
billion dollars, narrowed with the help of surging sales of
commercial aircraft to China.
</P>
<P>
Exports in April continued to rise, edging up 0.2 percent to an
all-time high of 78.4 billion dollars. However, imports rose even
more, up 0.9 percent to 86.7 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
In April, the biggest deficit as usual was with Japan, up 5.1
percent to 4.8 billion dollars, the highest since 4.9 billion
dollars last October. The deficit rose even further in May, based
on figures released earlier this week by the Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
The country continued to have trade deficits with its North
American Free Trade Agreement partners, although at a slower pace.
</P>
<P>
The imbalance with Canada ebbed 26.3 percent to 970 million
dollars, lowest since 900 million dollars in March 1995. Exports
of 13.3 billion dollars and imports of 14.3 billion dollars were
the highest on record with any country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the trade gap with the southern neighbor Mexico fell
5 percent to 1.4 billion dollars, led by a record 5.7 billion
dollars in exports.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. foreign oil imports rose 3.3 percent to 5.6 billion
dollars, despite the lowest price in more than a year. Crude oil
prices dropped to 17.17 dollars a barrel, the third straight
decline, but were offset by a 6.8 percent jump in volume to 250
million barrels.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, the country's trade gap has been running at a
112.4 billion dollar annual rate, even wider than the revised 111
billion dollars in 1996 and worst since 115.8 billion dollars in
1988. The largest gap of 152.9 billion dollars was recorded in
1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
