<HEADLINE> Pakistan Wants to Resolve All Issues With India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan is committed to finding
solutions to all outstanding issues with India including the core
issue of Kashmir through dialogue, a senior Pakistani diplomat
said today.
</P>
<P>
"The solution to the Kashmir problem is indispensable for
durable peace and for diverting the energies to the development
and poverty alleviation in the region," said Shamshad Ahmed,
Pakistan's foreign secretary, in an interview with the Associated
Press of Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad made the remarks on the eve of a new round of foreign
secretary-level talks between India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
"We think structured and synchronized discussions are a must
for achieving real progress on all issues," he said.
</P>
<P>
There are no "quick fixes" to resolve the issues between the
two countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Shamshad said Pakistan would convey its concern to India during
the forthcoming talks over the reported deployment of medium-range
ballistic Prithvi missiles by India near its border with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
genuinely believes that economic development in the region would
be possible only if all outstanding issues were resolved through
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The new round of foreign secretary-level talks will begin here
on Friday and is expected to conclude next Monday. The decision
to continue the dialogue was made by the prime ministers of India
and Pakistan at their meeting in the Maldives last month on the
sidelines of a regional summit.
</P>
<P>
The previous round of the talks was held in New Delhi in March
after a gap of three years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
