<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian-Iraqi Trade Not to Be Affected: Aziz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz reiterated here today that the Jordanian-Iraqi trade ties
would not be affected by any factors.
</P>
<P>
Aziz made the remarks at a meeting with Jordan's Prime Minister
Abdul Salam Majali this morning.
</P>
<P>
Aziz's statement seems intended to ease the anxieties of
Jordanian businessmen who fear of losing business opportunities
with Iraq. The sanction-impaled country submitted a request
today to the U.N. for the approval of its import of food and
medicine through Abu Al-Shamat, a Syrian-Iraqi border crossing.
</P>
<P>
The border point has been closed since Iraq severed diplomatic
relations with Syria for its siding with Iran in the Iran-Iraq War
in early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade ties between Iraq and Syria were resumed
only recently.
</P>
<P>
The reopening of the Syrian-Iraqi border crossing will
certainly impact Jordan's exports to Iraq, which has been Jordan's
largest trade partner for years, local newspaper Jordan Times
today quoted Mohammad Dalabieh, head of Ports Corporation of
Jordan, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian export of goods and services to Iraq totaled 220
million U.S. dollars in value in 1996. The figure even hit 400
million dollars in previous years.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian businessmen also feared that Jordan would make less
money from transit trade bound for Iraq if the Iraqi request can
be approved by the U.N.
</P>
<P>
Iraq now import goods mainly through its borders with Jordan
and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
If the request is approved, global exporters, especially the
European ones, could first transport goods to Syria's
Mediterranean ports of Tartoos and Laziqiyeh and then carry the
goods by trucks into Iraq through Abu Al-Shamat border point,
local paper said.
</P>
<P>
This is a short and low-cost transportation route to Iraq in
comparison with the one that passes the Egyptian Suez Canal,
Jordan's Red Sea port of Aqaba and finally the Jordanian-Iraqi
border.
</P>
<P>
Along this route, Iraq imported civilian goods and military
equipment during the Iraq-Iran war and Jordan made more than one
billion dollars every year from entrepot trade through Aqaba port
bound for Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's businessmen were concerned that the reopening of the
border point might also affect a trade protocol signed by Jordan
and Iraq at the beginning of this year. The protocol worth 255
million dollars is exempt from the U.N. imposed sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, some Jordanian officials insisted that the
Jordanian-Iraqi trade will not be affected by the reopening of the
Syrian-Iraqi border.
</P>
<P>
Whatever happens, the trade protocol will be honored and in
fact, parts of it have already been materialized, said a Jordanian
official who prefers not be identified. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
