<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civil Engineering for HK New Airport Railway Nearly Complete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Ninety percent of civil
engineering work for the Airport Railway has been finished, with
the focus shifted to interior decoration and equipment
installation.
</P>
<P>
The Airport Railway is being built to provide special service
for the new international airport of Hong Kong, which will replace
the overloaded Kai Tak Airport.
</P>
<P>
The railway, which is designed to be 34 kilometers long and
will also provide mass transit commuter service, is believed to be
the first of its kind across the world.
</P>
<P>
The two different services have been named "Airport Express"
and "Tung Chung Line," respectively.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Mass Transit Railway Corporation, which
was designated by the Hong Kong government as the railway's
builder, said today that 70 percent of the railway track has been
laid, and that trains for the Tung Chung Line have started test
run.
</P>
<P>
"At the current construction speed, the railway will go into
operation before June in 1998," the official said.
</P>
<P>
The Airport Express and the Tung Chung Line are the fourth and
fifth railways to be built and operated by the Mass Transit
Railway Corporation, following the MTR Island Line, MTR Tsuen Wan
and MTR Kwun Tong.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong new airport is scheduled to open in April, 1998,
and the Airport Railway will start operation two months later.
</P>
<P>
It will take 23 minutes for a train to run through the railway,
which will have eight kilometers of tunnels and six kilometers of
elevated line.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
