<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Sure to Qualify for Euro, Institute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Germany is set to miss the budgetary
target for joining the planned single European currency -- Euro,
but this will not prevent it from qualifying, a German economic
institute predicted today.
</P>
<P>
IFO (Institute for Economic Studies) President Karl Heinrich
Oppenlaender said in Munich that Germany's national budget deficit
for 1997 would be 120 billion marks (70 billion U.S. dollars), or
3.2 percent of gross domestic product (GDP), higher than the 3
percent required by Euro standards.
</P>
<P>
However, he said that even with such a deficit, Germany would
not be denied entry to the single currency, thanks to a softening
of the Euro terms which seems increasingly likely.
</P>
<P>
He also predicted that if Euro was to be launched punctually on
January 1, 1999, though on a softer footing, the German mark and
other European currencies would be put under remarkable pressure
to depreciate, which in turn would encourage European central
banks to raise interests rates. The overall effect would be
unfavorable for the German economy.
</P>
<P>
In case of a delay in launching Euro, European countries could
then shift their attention to more active employment policy and
ease up on budgetary restraint.
</P>
<P>
The result would almost certainly be a surge in the German
mark's value, which would threaten the country's exports and its
chances of reducing double-digit unemployment, Oppenlaender said.
</P>
<P>
The best way leading to Euro would be to pursue a credible
consolidation strategy of budget, he added.
</P>
<P>
The IFO institute also predicted that Germany could expect a
GDP growth of between 2 and 2.5 percent for 1997 and a growth of
up to 2.75 percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Germany's unemployment figure would increase to 4.3 million in
1997, IFO said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Executive Council Members Confident in HK's future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Three members of the Executive
Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) to
be established on July 1 expressed their full confidence in Hong
Kong's future in a forum held with the media here today.
</P>
<P>
The three members, former Chief Justice Sir Ti Liang Yang,
Chung Shui-Ming, and Raymond K.F. Ch'ien, met overseas journalists
who came to cover the handover of Hong Kong in a forum held by the
Better Hong Kong Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The forum was chaired by Nellie Fong Kut-man, an Executive
Council member and chairman of the Executive Committee of the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of Hong Kong's realities and post-handover prospects,
the members shared the view that in accordance with the "one
country, two systems" principle, Hong Kong will maintain the
stability of its social and economic systems as a special
administration region of China, noting that there is no need to
worry about drastic changes.
</P>
<P>
Sir Ti Liang Yang said that Hong Kong's present legal system
has been tested and developed over a long period of time, and as a
result has been accepted by the public.
</P>
<P>
"The legal system has been included in the Basic Law and will
continue to be implemented after July 1," he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his confidence in the independence of Hong Kong's
legal system, the integrity of its judges and the professional
quality of its lawyers after the handover.
</P>
<P>
Chung said he is optimistic that Hong Kong will continue to
retain its status as an international financial center after July
1, while an increasingly open inland area will provide more
development opportunities for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Ch'ien, who is also a member of Hong Kong's present Executive
Council, said that China's administrative departments are becoming
increasingly open, modern and democratic.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Hong Kong people will feel quite at ease as
residents of a region that is part of a country which enjoys a
bright future and is advancing toward modernization.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
