<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to Set Out Strategies for Training Young People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) is to set
out five strategies to develop apprenticeship in member states so
as to improve young people's chances of finding jobs, media
reports said today.
</P>
<P>
The initiative has been proposed to the European Council for
approval by Edith Cresson, EU Commissioner for Research, Education
and Training, and Padraig Flynn, Commissioner for Employment and
Social Affairs.
</P>
<P>
The five strategies include extending and developing
apprenticeship, enhancing the quality of training, encouraging the
mobility of apprentices, involving the social partners in
apprenticeship training and defining and implementing truly
European apprenticeship strategies.
</P>
<P>
Reports say that apprenticeship is a faster route to a job
provided that it is of high quality, meets the needs of companies
and provides sufficiently flexible training to allow life-long
adaptation to industrial changes.
</P>
<P>
In Belgium, the unemployment rate for former apprentices is 16
percent while the national youth jobless rate is 20 percent. In
Ireland, the placement rate for apprentices is between 95 and 100
percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
