<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Fully Decked Out for Handover </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The skyline and streets of Hong
Kong Island and Kowloon have been decked out with lights, lanterns
and other decorative objects featuring Hong Kong's return to its
motherland since the beginning of this month.
</P>
<P>
The proposal of "greeting Hong Kong's return to China with
bright lights" put forward by the Hong Kong Tourist Association
has received active responses from all social sectors in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Numerous high-rises and hotels along the Victoria Harbor,
including Shun Tak Center, City Plaza and the Harbor View Holiday
Inn, have been decorated with colorful lights and neon designs to
welcome Hong Kong's return to the motherland, greatly adding to
the festive atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
The Urban Services Department has allocated 14 million US
dollars to beautify the city with lights and lanterns to give the
city an atmosphere of jubilation for the handover.
</P>
<P>
Wong Kian Shan, the manager of a local lights and design
company, said his company has received a huge number of orders
from prestigious hotels and companies since the beginning of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The majority of customers requested designs of the white
dolphin, the mascot of Hong Kong, dragons, giant pandas,
fireworks, bauhinia and the slogan of "Celebrate the return of
Hong Kong to the motherland" in Chinese characters.
</P>
<P>
The building of the China Insurance Company bears the design of
a bauhinia and a map of China made up of lights, five red stars
sparkling amid the design.
</P>
<P>
A local resident said, "Hong Kong these days is brighter than
it is during Chinese new year and Christmas holidays."
</P>
<P>
Outside the Eaton Hotel Hong Kong in Kowloon is a behemoth of
lights and patterns forming a white dolphin and the regional
emblem of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region. The design
is so big that people can view it from across the harbor on Hong
Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
A 3.5-km-long dragon bearing two million light bulbs is being
installed on Nathan Road, Kowloon. The dragon's head faces the
Victoria Harbor at Tsim Sha Tsui and its tail reaches the end of
the road. In length, the dragon can well claim a place in the
Guinness record book. The dragon is scheduled to be lighted at
the end of this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
