<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Concerned with UNSCOM Delays </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Iraq has expressed concern over
the U.N. delay in forwarding the findings in the examination of
remnants of its destroyed missile engines, according to the
official Iraqi News Agency (INA) today.
</P>
<P>
The concern of the Iraqi government was voiced by Deputy Prime
Minister Tariq Aziz in a letter Wednesday to Rolf Ekeus, executive
chairman of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on dismantling
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Aziz argued that some preliminary results of the examination
should be submitted to Iraq within weeks and that the final
results should be ready by August 1997.
</P>
<P>
About 100 proscribed missile engines of Iraq were transported
to the United States and France in early March for analysis, in
order to determine whether they are from the Soviet-made Scud
missiles or the locally-made "useless" ones.
</P>
<P>
This move was taken in accordance with a joint statement
reached late in February by Ekeus and Aziz, which said the
U.N. commission will inform the Iraqi government of the findings
in the analysis when they are available.
</P>
<P>
The delay is "unobjective, costly and is meant to delay the
closing of (Iraq's) weapons files indefinitely," said Aziz,
pointing out its consequence is "the continuation of the
(U.N.-imposed) embargo (on Iraq) and the sufferings" of the Iraqi
people.
</P>
<P>
Iraq is not allowed to have weapons of mass destruction,
including missiles with ranges beyond 150 kilometers, after its
troops were defeated by the U.S.-led allied forces in the 1991
Gulf War triggered by its invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The UNSCOM in charge of scrapping the weapons suspects Iraq
still possesses a considerable number of the missiles. However,
Baghdad denies concealing any such weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
