<HEADLINE> China Makes 13-Billion-Bytes-Per-Second Super Computer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- China has developed a new super
computer called the "Yinhe-3," capable of performing 13 billion
calculations per second, marking a breakthrough for the country in
developing large-scale computer systems.
</P>
<P>
The state-of-the-art design by the Computer Institute under the
National Defense Science and Technology University passed State
appraisal here today.
</P>
<P>
The computer is able to calculate at a speed of up to 13
billion bytes per second and is more than 10 times more powerful
than its predecessor, the "Yinhe-2," developed in 1992. But the
size of the "Yinhe-3" is only one-sixth of the "Yinhe-2".
</P>
<P>
The super computer adopts the latest international standards,
allowing all its processors to operate simultaneously, and the
system can be expanded with additional parts.
</P>
<P>
Its overall functions, efficiency and powerful network design
are up to the world advanced level, claimed the appraisal
committee, which was composed of academicians from the Chinese
Academy of Sciences and Chinese Academy of Engineering and other
prestigious scholars in this field.
</P>
<P>
But what stands out most about this system is its
flexibility: it can be easily altered into a smaller version able
to "think" at a speed of several hundred million bytes per second,
or into an even bigger and more powerful setup than its original
capacity, depending on the needs of users, according to the
experts.
</P>
<P>
They believe that such a breakthrough in the hi-tech field will
greatly promote the country's economic development, defense
building, and science and technology progress.
</P>
<P>
The computer developer, the National Defense Science and
Technology University, has also created software for weather
forecasts, earthquake research and others fields of scientific
study.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fast Developing Exhibition Industry in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center has, for years, been the symbol of local fast
developing exhibition industry, though it has become a media focus
for its newly completed extension project, the venue of the grand
ceremonies of Hong Kong's historic handover.
</P>
<P>
One of the world's prime locations for conventions and
exhibitions, Hong Kong last year hosted more than 700
international conferences, over 60 major international business
and trade exhibitions, fairs, auctions and other business
activities.
</P>
<P>
The utilization rate of the center's exhibition hall is the
highest in the world and the reservation for exhibition
facilities in the center has run through 1998, according to a
senior manager in charge of exhibitions at the Hong Kong Trade
Development Council.
</P>
<P>
The history of Hong Kong's exhibition dated back to the late
1970s when its textile industry took off. The fast development of
its toy and timepiece manufacturing, and electronic industries
subsequently created conditions for the holding of comprehensive
exhibitions in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
By 1991, the then area of the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center began to fall short of demand. And it is
expected that the expanded Center with a total area of 60,000 sq.
m. will only be able to cope with the demand before the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts said that Hong Kong's exhibition industry has
drawn much of its vitality from its unique advantages in Asia --
the easy accesses provided by its transport and communications,
preferential customs tariffs on imports and exports, and free flow
of foreign currency.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has a top venue worldwide for specialized exhibitions
such as those of gifts and presents, timepieces, jewelry,
garments, and furs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
