<HEADLINE> Iran Sends Envoy to Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 19 (Xinhua) -- An envoy sent by Iranian
government to Iraqi President Saddam Hussein arrived here today on
a week-long visit.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Ali Reza Marandi, Iranian Health Minister, was believed to
be the first Iranian ranking official to come to Baghdad over the
past several year.
</P>
<P>
The official Iraqi News Agency didn't give any details about
the envoy's mission here. But observers believe this visit is a
friendly gesture aimed at improving relations between the two
countries under new circumstances of the Middle East political
arena.
</P>
<P>
They also noted that the visit came after Mohammad Khatami,
said to be a moderate clergy, was elected Iran's new president
with a landslide victory in the elections last month.
</P>
<P>
Iraq and Iran, long-term foes in the Gulf region, fought an
eight-year war from 1980-88 with neither coming out the winner.
However, their diplomatic ties were resumed in 1990 at the height
of the Gulf crisis, which was triggered by Iraq's invasion of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The two are embroiled in disputes over two pending issues: the
exchange of POWs of their protracted war and the return of Iraq's
planes which flew to Iran during the Gulf War to avoid the attack
of the U.S.-led allies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
