<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Macao Can Learn From HK's Smooth Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Macao can learn a lot from Hong
Kong's smooth transition, a leading Macao businessman said here
in Macao recently.
</P>
<P>
Ma Man Kei, president of the Macao Chamber of Commerce, said
in an exclusive interview with Xinhua that Hong Kong's smooth
transition serves both as an encouragement and a model for Macao.
</P>
<P>
"Today's Hong Kong is tomorrow's Macao," he said. "Hong Kong's
smooth return to the motherland will influence Macao
positively. Macao can learn a lot from Hong Kong's experience."
</P>
<P>
For instance, he said, Macao should quicken its pace in the
localization of the middle and senior ranking civil service to
pave the way for the top civil service to "stride over" the
handover to the motherland in 1999, since top civil servants of
non-Chinese nationality in Macao are not allowed to stay on after
the return.
</P>
<P>
In Hong Kong, nearly all the top civil service will retain
their jobs after the return on July 1, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Very few positions of the middle and senior civil service in
Macao are now held by local Chinese people. The Chinese side has
repeatedly urged the Portuguese side to step up the localization
process.
</P>
<P>
Having lived in Macao since 1941, Ma said he is very happy that
 Hong Kong returns to the motherland. He attributed that to an
increasingly stronger motherland.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's return to the motherland is a dream of all Chinese
people throughout the world," he said. "July 1 will be the most
glorious day as the humiliation China has suffered from over the
past century will be removed."
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong's return in a peaceful way demonstrates that China
has become stronger and stronger over the past decades," added Ma,
who will be a member of the central delegation to attend the
handover ceremony in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Ma, 78, a vice-chairman of the National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC),
believes that Hong Kong would have a bright future after returning.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong will remain prosperous and stable, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong enjoys favorable conditions in its port, traffic and
climate, and has laid a good foundation for further development,"
he said. "With support from the motherland and with the
implementation of the 'one country, two systems' policy and the
Basic Law, Hong Kong will continue its economic boom."
</P>
<P>
Ma highly praised the concept of "one country, two systems",
saying it is an pioneering idea in handling bilateral issues left
over from history, and is "pragmatic and scientific."
</P>
<P>
"It takes the interests of most citizens in Hong Kong and Macao
 into account, thus contributing to a continuous prosperity and
stability in both places," he said, adding that "I believe the
strategic idea will also be important in handling the Taiwan
issue." 
</P>
</TEXT>
