<HEADLINE> Japanese PM Leaves for Denver Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto left here today for Denver, Colorado of the United
States to attend a three-day annual summit of the Group of Seven
(G-7) industrialized countries and Russia.
</P>
<P>
At the summit which begins on Friday evening, Hashimoto is
expected to exchange views with other leaders on a wide range of
global topics, including environmental preservation, aging
population, unemployment, nuclear energy safety and measures to
combat terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The Denver summit, the 23rd one of G-7, will bring together
leaders from Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, the
United States and Russia.
</P>
<P>
On the eve of the summit, Hashimoto will hold talks separately
with U.S. President Bill Clinton, Russian President Boris Yeltsin,
and leaders of Germany, Britain and France, Foreign Ministry
officials said.
</P>
<P>
Prior to his departure, Hashimoto told a news briefing that he
would press Yeltsin to reach an agreement on a bilateral
territorial row over four Russia-held islands off Japan's northern
island of Hokkaido.
</P>
<P>
After the Denver summit, Hashimoto will fly to New York to
attend a special session of the U.N. General Assembly on the
environment on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He will also visit the Netherlands and Norway before returning
to Tokyo on June 28. 
</P>
