<HEADLINE> EU Official Advocates Agreement on Animal Trapping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- An international agreement to ban
the worst "leg-hold" traps and enforce humane standards on the
rest will do much more for animal welfare than a mere ban on fur
imports, a European Union (EU) official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Sir Leon Brittan, EU trade commissioner, made the remark as EU
ministers are preparing for a decision Thursday and Friday on the
question of curbing the use of animal traps.
</P>
<P>
He said that a mere import ban might have instant appeal, but
it could prove unenforceable, and would send the fur business in
search of lucrative markets elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
The first-ever international trapping standard, negotiated by
the EU with Canada and Russia, will be aimed at cutting cruelty to
wild animals by forcing Canada, Russia and the EU to abolish the
worst forms of trapping.
</P>
<P>
EU officials note that trappers in the remotest corners of
Siberia and the Yukon are unlikely to change their age-old ways
unless they are obliged to do so by their own governments, and
helped in the process.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt in my mind that trapping can be a cruel
business, and that Europe has a duty to improve animal welfare,"
Brittan said.
</P>
<P>
The EU ministers are facing two options -- either to ban all
imports of fur into Europe from countries where "leg-hold" traps
are used until trapping methods are changed, or to approve a set
of rules that would force all trappers to use only the most humane
methods, and face penalties if they do not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Macao Foreign Trade Up in First Four Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Macao foreign trade grew vigorously
in the first four months of the year, with both imports and
exports increasing remarkably.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures released by the Macao Census and Statistics
Department show that between January and April, Macao exported 4.7
billion patacas (about 595 million US dollars) worth of goods, up
16.4 percent from the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The imports for the period reached 5.1 billion patacas (about
645.6 million US dollars), up 7.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
As a result, a trade deficit of 468 million patacas (about 59.2
million US dollars) was recorded. That was an increase of 37.7
percent from the deficit in the same 1996 period.
</P>
<P>
Of the total exports, textile and garment products accounted
for 83.8 percent, while the proportion of non-textile products,
including machinery and equipment, footwear and concrete,
continued to shrink.
</P>
<P>
About three-fourth of Macao exports went to the United States
and the European Union, while the source of Macao's imported goods
concentrated on the Asian-Pacific region, mostly, the Chinese
inland areas, Taiwan, Hong Kong, Japan, Australia and South Korea.
</P>
<P>
The imports of capital goods rose 19.3 percent, raw materials
and semi-finished goods 10.1 percent, and fuel and lubricating oil
7.1 percent, but the imports of consumption goods dropped 0.04
percent.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the foreign trade growth has indicated that
the local economy is recovering after a two-year-long slowdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EC Proposes Action Plan for Pollution Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, has adopted a proposal for a
five-year action program on the prevention of diseases which are
caused, provoked and aggravated by environmental pollution.
</P>
<P>
The proposal was put forward by Padraig Flynn, EU commissioner
for employment and social affairs, and Ritt Bjerregaard,
commissioner for environment, nuclear safety and civil protection,
says a press release issued here today.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that one in three Europeans suffer from an
allergy, with a recent study indicating that the situation is
worsening at an "alarming" rate -- one in two people are predicted
to be affected soon.
</P>
<P>
The Commission has identified a three-pronged strategy to
prevent pollution-related diseases -- the reduction of pollutants
by taking action at their source, action to limit people's
exposure to pollutants and mitigation of adverse health effects on
individuals exposed to pollutants.
</P>
<P>
The proposed program will be reportedly subject to the
co-decision procedure of the European Parliament and the Council
of Ministers, and it will run from 1999 to 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
