<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australians Live Longer, Marry Later </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Australians are living longer,
marrying later, having fewer children and becoming healthier while
the gap between the rich and poor is growing, the Australian
Bureau of Statistics said today.
</P>
<P>
More women are marrying younger men and one-parent families and
families with no children are increasing.
</P>
<P>
The bureau's Australian Social Trends 1997 collated information
on virtually all aspects of the life of the 18 million
Australians, including work and income, family structure,
immigration and crime.
</P>
<P>
Australians' median age in 1996 was 34, up from 31 a decade
earlier. The proportion of people aged 65 and over was 12 percent,
up from 10.5 percent, and is projected to hit 23 percent in 2051.
</P>
<P>
Children aged up to 14 made up 21 percent of the population,
down from 23 percent in 1986, and are expected to fall to 17
percent by the middle of the next century. They increased by 1
percent between 1975 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
But the number of older Australians went up by 78 percent in
the same period.
</P>
<P>
The median age of new mothers was 28.6 years in 1995. Almost 14
percent of all births were to women over 35, up from 7.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
More babies were born out of wedlock, rising from 15.5 percent
of all births in 1985 to 26.6 percent in 1995, and most now have
the father's name on the birth certificate.
</P>
<P>
One-parent families are approaching 20 percent of all families,
with two-thirds of single parents divorced, separated or widowed.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, men married at a median age of 27.3 years and women at
25.3 years. The median age rose rapidly in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Families with children are now likely to have two incomes, but
the proportion with neither parent working has also increased.
</P>
<P>
The statistics showed that more people were born overseas, from
21 percent in 1986 to 23 percent in 1996, and people from Asian
countries represent a growing segment of the population.
</P>
<P>
Britain and Ireland remain the major source of Australia's
immigrants, although their proportion of all migrants dropped from
41 percent in 1976 to 29 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
They are Followed by New Zealand, Italy, the former Yugoslav
republics, Vietnam, Greece, Germany, China, Hong Kong, the
Netherlands, Malaysia and the Philippines. The only Asian nation
on this list 20 years ago was India.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 9 Killed in Floods in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Nine people were killed in floods
in northeastern and northwestern Iran in the past 48 hours,
Iran's official news agency IRNA reported today.
</P>
<P>
It said that villages of Shandiz area in Khorasan province and
Aslandouz district in Ardebil province had been flooded following
heavy rainfall since Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the Red Crescent Society in Khorasan province
said Wednesday night that eight persons were killed in the
Karakht Village of Shandiz.
</P>
<P>
Some 20 villages of Aslandouz suffered heavy damages as a
result of the floods Wednesday. One person was killed while 2,500
hectares of farmlands and 5,000 hectares of pastures were
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, some roads and bridges were also
destroyed by the floods.
</P>
<P>
Rescue teams are busy carrying out relief operations, using
helicopters in several villages.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the heavy rain and a hailstorm damaged several
villages in Khalkhal in Ardebil province on the same day, but no
reports were available on the extent of damage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
