<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Film on Opium War Popular in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- "Opium War," a movie that began
showing in Hong Kong on June 14, took in 926,000 Hong Kong dollars
in box office receipt in the first three days of screening, local
sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
The movie, which was produced by an independent film studio
based in southwest China's Sichuan Province, tells the story of
the Anglo-Chinese Opium War in the early 1840s. One direct result
of the war is the 156-year British occupation of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The movie earned 170,000 Hong Kong dollars on the first day of
screening, and its box office receipt jumped to 300,000 Hong Kong
dollars the next day.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee-hwa, the first Chief Executive of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), Zhang Junsheng,
deputy-director of Xinhua News Agency Hong Kong Branch, and Rita
Fan Hsu Lai Tai, chairwoman of the HKSAR Provisional Legislative
Council, attended the movie's premiere in the Hong Kong Convention
and Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
Tung said the movie has a special significance at this historic
moment when Hong Kong is going to return to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
The movie has won favorable comments from local movie critics,
who praise it for "successfully depicting a historical event from
a modern perspective while preserving the tradition of historical
movies produced in China's interior areas."
</P>
<P>
"The movie reproduces history, and denounces the decadence of
China's feudal dynasty and the invasion against China by British
imperialists," a local moviegoer commented. "I appreciate the
expertise of the director."
</P>
<P>
"Opium War" was directed by Xie Jin, a veteran film director in
Shanghai who enjoys worldwide reputation.
</P>
<P>
With the date of Hong Kong's handover approaching, movies and
TV shows on related subjects produced by local and mainland
studios have frequently appeared in local movie houses and on
local television.
</P>
<P>
TVB, a major local TV station, is now airing in prime time "The
Story of Hong Kong," a TV series on Hong Kong's vicissitudes over
the past century, which was produced in China's interior area.
</P>
<P>
 
</P>
</TEXT>
