<HEADLINE> Boundary of Administration between Guangdong, Hong Kong Cleared </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A memorandum of understanding
concerning the boundary of administration between Guangdong
Province and Hong Kong was officially signed here today.
</P>
<P>
Delegations from Guangdong and Hong Kong have reached agreement
on the memorandum after 13 rounds of negotiations, which started
on April 8, 1988, in the spirit of mutual understanding and mutual
accommodation.
</P>
<P>
Signing the memorandum were Xiao Jinzhe, head of the Guangdong
delegation and vice-director of the Foreign Affairs Office of the
province, and John Ashton, head of the Hong Kong delegation and
Deputy Political Advisor.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to divide the Deep Bay and the Mirs Bay
with the center lines of the water surfaces. On the sea area south
of Hong Kong, a boundary line was drawn one nautical mile offshore
from the southwestern part of Lantau Island, as well as the
southern part of Soko Islands, and the southern part of the Po Toi
Islands. Center lines also were chosen to mark the boundary in
narrow waters.
</P>
<P>
The land boundary line will reach to the center point of
rivers, roads, irrigation canals and ditches, and valleys.
</P>
<P>
Xiao and Ashton initialed the memorandum on the boundary of
administration on January 17, 1997, in Shenzhen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
