<HEADLINE> China's Vice-Premier on "One Country, Two Systems" (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The People's Daily, China's
leading national newspaper, today published an article by Chinese
vice-premier and foreign minister Qian Qichen, entitled "Adhering
to the Principle of 'One Country, Two Systems' in the Long Term."
</P>
<P>
Following are excerpts from the article, which is Qian's
speech Wednesday at a meeting to discuss Deng Xiaoping's theory on
"peaceful reunification" and "one country, two systems". Qian is
also the chairman of the Preparatory Committee for the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
Qian reviewed that it was with Deng Xiaoping's great concept of
"one country, two systems," that the Hong Kong question has been
finally perfectly resolved. "The Chinese government has upheld the
concept and has made great efforts for the establishment of SAR in
steps during the 13-year-long transitional period," Qian
said, adding that "Practices in the past years have proven the
truthfulness of Deng's unique thoughts."
</P>
<P>
The issue following Hong Kong's return to the motherland
is to unswervingly safeguard the long-term prosperity and
stability of the SAR, which can be considered both "a strategic
task for China and an issue concerning the international
community," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
The key to the issue is to keep the principle of "one country,
two systems" unchanged in the long run. "The Sino-British Joint
Declaration and the Basic Law of Hong Kong SAR has clearly
promulgated that the principle is to remain 'unchanged for 50
years," which means unchanged for a long period of time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Loans to Bangladesh, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Manila-based Asian Development
Bank (ADB) today approved loans totaling 107.1 million U.S.
dollars to Bangladesh and Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
The ADB said in a news release that the loan to Bangladesh will
help finance a livestock development project in which
beneficiaries, non-governmental organizations and government play
key roles.
</P>
<P>
The project will give more than 350,000 households,
particularly poor and landless women, in northwest and
north-central Bangladesh an opportunity to earn money by rearing
chickens, cattle and goats.
</P>
<P>
Of the total loans, 87.4 million dollars will go to Indonesia
for a communicable diseases control project to intensify efforts
to reduce the diseases in the country.
</P>
<P>
More than 17 million people will benefit from the project which
will improve the delivery of health services in the country, the
bank said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Vice-Premier on "One Country, Two Systems" (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Qian gave five reasons for adhering to the principle:
</P>
<P>
First, he considered it a decision made for the long-term good
of China. China has set a goal to quadruple its gross domestic
product to 1,000-1,200 billion US dollars before the year
2000. Accordingly, guaranteeing the prosperity of Hong Kong, a
nexus for the country to the international market, is necessary
for China's best interests.
</P>
<P>
Second, he said, the eventual target is to reunite China by
peaceful means. The solution of the Hong Kong question is
considered a giant leap towards the reunification of the whole
country.
</P>
<P>
"After Hong Kong's return, China will solve the Macao problem,
and finally realize the reunification across the Taiwan Strait with
the principle of "peaceful reunification based on one country, two
systems'," Qian said. This is not a choice based on emotion, but
rather a practical consideration of both Hong Kong's history and
current situation.
</P>
<P>
Third, the bottom line is that the policy must not be changed
by either side. "This means that the inland area will not alter
its socialist system and Hong Kong retains its capitalist
system. The two systems co-exist in one country," Qian noted. "The
condition for keeping Hong Kong's capitalism is that the inland
area sticks to socialism."
</P>
<P>
The fourth reason for carrying out the principle is that it
lets Hong Kong people govern Hong Kong. "The mentality of old
colonialists considered Chinese people incapable of governing
Hong Kong well. However, the prosperity of Hong Kong should be
attributed to Hong Kong people, of which the Chinese form the
majority," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Finally, the principle requires a high degree of autonomy in
the SAR, which ultimately will lead to China's reunification. "In
that context, the operation of the capitalist system in a small
region is beneficial for the development of socialism as a whole,"
Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Qian concluded by summing up two fundamental characteristics of
the principle: it is the outcome of the Chinese Communist Party's
practice to "seek truth from facts," and it can be used to solve
other controversial issues in other parts of the world.
</P>
<P>
"It was an idea born in China, but it can be used to tackle
certain international problems," Qian pointed out.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
