<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Chinese Municipality To Balance Economy and Environment (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Chongqing is one of China's six old industrial bases, and has
decided to combine six of its pillar industries to make
three: automobiles and motorcycles, chemical industry, and
metallurgy, with priority being given to the fine chemical
industry and nonferrous metal precision work, which cause less
pollution.
</P>
<P>
The city has begun to increase its efforts to develop new
pillar industries that pollute less, for the next century, in
electronics, information, building materials, tourism, and
foodstuff.
</P>
<P>
It is also doing its best to develop natural gas and
hydroelectric power, and expects to build a nuclear power station
after the year 2000 as part of its effort to cut down on coal
consumption, which accounts for 75 percent of the current energy
structure.
</P>
<P>
By 2010, Chongqing will stop using coal for housing and the
service sector to get more than 50 percent of its energy to be
clean. Two large steel plants are moving out of the city proper as
part of this.
</P>
<P>
During the same period, the city will spend more heavily on
building a sewage treatment plant with a 1.2-million-ton daily
capacity along the upper reaches of the Three Gorges Dam, and make
sure that drainage into the Yangtze River by all industrial
enterprises is clean enough.
</P>
<P>
It is expected to bring the density of sulphur dioxide to 0.25
mg per cu.m. at that time, and have all drinking water sources
meet certain standards.
</P>
<P>
"We are doing all we can to develop the economy and improve the
environment simultaneously, and I believe we will do a better job
in environmental protection as our city grows stronger
economically," the mayor concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
