<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Successfully Cultivate Plants With Saltwater </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
successfully cultivated plants with saltwater in the Taklimakan
desert, in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The moving desert has a severe environment, with sharp
temperature differences between day and night and massive storms
of sand and dust, that prevents the Tarim oil field from being
further developed.
</P>
<P>
The headquarters for the Tarim oil field exploration and the
Lanzhou Desert Research Institute under the Chinese Academy of
Sciences began to jointly conduct pilot experiments for
afforestation at the heart of the desert in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Experiments have also been conducted for cultivating vegetables
and grasses in the desert, and techniques have been developed for
making use of the local desert and underground saltwater resources
to cultivate vegetables and other plants.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists found that obnoxious substances of the sandy
soil and saltwater will be wiped out when they are put together,
and the mixture can be turned into a kind of useful land and water
resource.
</P>
<P>
"The harmful substance in the salty water can be quickly
dissolved in the sandy soil, and the soil has the characteristics
of not absorbing salt, which is suitable for planting crops," said
Gao Qianzhao, a leading scentist of the research project.
</P>
<P>
Research has found that the plants cultivated by bitter
saltwater are growing better than the one cultivated by fresh
water, which is attributed to the sharp temperature difference in
the Tarim desert. The difference has enabled the sandy soil to
better condense the moisture content in the saltwater.
</P>
<P>
The experimental zone in the desert, where nothing used to
grow, has developed an 0.3 ha of greenhouse vegetable garden, 1.6
ha of forest, and a shelter tree belt of 120 meters in length,
setting up an entire saltwater irrigation system.
</P>
<P>
More than 30 kinds of vegetables and crops have been
cultivated, with some hitting the country's record of per-ha
production, such as 75,000 kg of tomatoes per ha, and 56,000 kg of
rapeseed per ha.
</P>
<P>
Experts have pointed out the successful cultivation of plants
by bitter saltwater has not only found ways to solve the living
problems of workers of the Tarim oil field, but also provided
valuable experiences for China to further develop desert areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
