<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Election of SAR Chief Executive Marks a New Era in HK (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A total of 31 people applied before the deadline set by the
Preparatory Committee (PC). The PC Executive Council, upon
examination of their qualifications, determined that eight of them
were qualified as contenders for candidacy.
</P>
<P>
On November 15, 1996, the Selection Committee held its first
plenary session in Hong Kong to select formal candidates for the
Chief Executive. The session was open to the public. Out of the
eight contenders for candidacy, Tung Chee Hwa, Yang Ti-Liang and
Woo Kwong-ching received, respectively, 206, 82 and 54 votes, to
become formal candidates for the first Chief Executive. The other
five were now out of the race.
</P>
<P>
On November 27, the Selection Committee heard policy speeches
of the three candidates at its second plenary session in Hong
Kong. Woo Kwong-ching, Tung Chee-Hwa and Yang Ti-liang outlined,
in the order chosen by lots, laid out their blueprints for the
administration of Hong Kong. They said they were competing for the
post out of a sense of a historical mission.
</P>
<P>
Afterwards, they attended four question-and-answer sessions
attended by various social sectors in Hong Kong. This provided a
basis for
vote-casting by members of the Selection Committee.
</P>
<P>
On December 11, in a solemn atmosphere, the 400 Selection
Committee members, representing more than six million Hong Kong
people, cast their votes for the first Chief Executive of the
HKSAR by secret ballot.
The event was covered by more than 300 Chinese and overseas
reporters and televised live to let all people in Hong Kong
witness the proceedings. The whole process was conducted under
supervisors designated by the PC Executive Council.
Tung Chee-Hwa, 59, won the election by winning 320 votes to
become the first Chief Executive of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in history, Hong Kong residents made their
own decision in choosing the highest-ranking official of the
region.
</P>
<P>
After the election, Tung said, "I will not underestimate
difficulties and challenges ahead. However, I have complete
confidence in the future of Hong Kong. I promise I would do my
utmost to create a better Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
On December 16, Chinese Premier Li Peng signed a State Council
order appointing Tung Chee-Hwa first Chief Executive of the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Election of the first Chief Executive of the HKSAR was
conducted under democratic, fair and open principles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
