<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Status as Global Shipping Center More Stable: Minister (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
All measures guarantee that Hong Kong's stance as international
shipping center will not be weakened but further stablized, Huang
predicted.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong last year handled 13.4 million containers, and ranked
as the world's leader for five years in a row. The hub is now also
an important entrepot for inland areas. Of the total container
transport volume, some 70 percent are related to inland areas.
</P>
<P>
The sound economic growth in inland areas is expected to
further boost the container transport to Hong Kong, he said.
</P>
<P>
The international harbors in the inland areas handled a
combined eight million containers last year. "The growth rate in
the first five months this year kept at 25 percent, ensuring the
steady flow of containers to Hong Kong," Huang noted.
</P>
<P>
Huang believed that the improving transport conditions in
inland areas, in particular in south China's Pearl River delta,
will further boost Hong Kong's shipping industry. "Guangdong now
has China's longest expressway network. The completion of certain
key projects, such as Guangzhou-Shenzhen Expressway,
Shenzhen-Shantou Expressway and other river harbors along the
Pearl River will give full play to Hong Kong's handling capacity,"
Huang said.
</P>
<P>
Huang revealed that his ministry has been in discussion with
relevant Hong Kong-based units on certain big transport
facilities, which, he believed, will be "mutual beneficial for
both inland areas and Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
As of the relationship between Shanghai, an emerging shipping
center, and Hong Kong, Huang said that "Shanghai is still in a
take-off period." The port handled 1.97 million containers last
year and the figure may hit 2.5 million this year, a rise of about
25 percent. "Even so, anyone can see it will take time and effort
for Shanghai to build up its strength and image," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
More importantly, the two centers are "compatible" for the two
have different service targets. "The targets of Hong Kong
concentrate on Pearl River Delta while Shanghai aims to provide
services for the whole Yangtze River valley," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Besides the title of communication minister, Huang also takes
the post of chairman of the board of China Merchants Steam
Navigation Company, one of the four major corporations funded by
the inland areas in Hong Kong. However, the company "seeks no
privileges or market dominance after Hong Kong's return to the
motherland," he said. "The role the company wants to play is to
contribute to the prosperity of Hong Kong."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
