<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Status as Global Shipping Center More Stable: Minister (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- "We will seriously deal with all
matters related to communications between the inland areas and
Hong Kong, an acknowledged international free port and shipping
center," Huang Zhendong, Chinese minister of communications told
Xinhua reporters in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
Huang said that the development of the transport industry, in
particular the oceanic shipping industry, is of vital importance
for the long-term prosperity and stability of Hong Kong after it
returns to the motherland.
</P>
<P>
He indicated that after the return of Hong Kong to the
motherland, the navigation routes between the inland areas, the
main body of the country, and Hong Kong, China's separate customs
territory, will be treated as "special regional routes,"
equivalent to foreign trade transport.
</P>
<P>
"In accordance with the Basic Law, and empowered by the central
government, the SAR government can independently maintain and
develop shipping ties with other countries or regions in the name
of 'Hong Kong, China'," Huang emphasized.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government will also be authorized to sign and
implement multi-lateral or bi-lateral navigation accords, and
establish official or semi-official navigation organs for handling
related matters.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will take effective measures to protect the
interests of Hong Kong in bi-lateral and multi-lateral navigation
problems after "thorough consultation with the SAR government or
relevant authorities" he added.
</P>
<P>
"Our ministry, however, will not interfere with SAR government
to settle navigation-related matters and will not set up organs
with administrative functions in Hong Kong after its return,"
Huang said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
