<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Grassroots Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Zhengzhou, June 19 (Xinhua) -- When the 3,000-plus deputies to
the National People's Congress gathered in Beijing in early April,
some 30 farmers in a small village in Henan Province, central
China, were busy debting issues surrounding the well-being of the
community.
</P>
<P>
The farmers were "people's representatives" directly elected by
the village's 370 households. Every ten families can choose one
for the villagers representative meeting that in turn elects the
village committee. They meet five to eight times a year to discuss
issues that touch everyone in the village.
</P>
<P>
The system is in use in different parts of rural China. In
Hunan Province's Xuchang City, for example, 1,892 villages out of
a total of 1,900 have set up representative meetings.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say that the trend indicates that Chinese farmers
begin to develop a sense of democracy, or political participation
when they have gained economic autonomy under the household
contract system adopted during the reform process.
</P>
<P>
One official explains: "The mandatory methods of collective
farming no longer work. There is the need for political reform."
Conflicts arose when farmers were not satisfied with decisions
made by village heads appointed by superiors, and in some places,
would try every way to give a hard time to village heads they
didn't like.
</P>
<P>
"All these years we have tried every way to meet farmers'
growing need for democratic participation," said an official in
Xuchang City.
</P>
<P>
In fact, the Standing Committee of the National People's
Congress, Chinese legislature, passed a village committee law in
1987, the essence of which is giving farmers the right to manage
their own affairs in accordance with certain laws and rules.
</P>
<P>
"The village representative meeting is the result of the
implementation of the law," the official noted. "Through the
directly elected representatives, farmers participate in the
decision-making process and have a very real sense of being their
own masters."
</P>
<P>
Zhaozhai Village made a lot of money by running several pig
farms, and when village heads thought the money should be used to
build an office building, their motion was voted down by 40
village representatives who insisted on using the money for a
school building.
</P>
<P>
Village representative meetings supervise village budgets but
they also put a check on village officials. Last year
representatives in one village in Xuchang City voted an official
out of office.
</P>
<P>
Xuchang has become an example in "villagers governing village
affairs", and people from other places have visited the villages
to learn from them.
</P>
<P>
This political participation by farmers, according to a senior
official, has led the government to open more avenues for
political participation for a broader segment of the rural
population.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Chinese Municipality To Balance Economy and Environment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Long known as the smog city,
Chongqing, China's fourth municipality -- after Beijing, Shanghai,
and Tianjin -- is taking steps to balance its ambitious long-range
economic development goals with environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The southwest China city, reportedly the world's largest,
with an area of 82,000 sq km and more than 30 million people,
plans to quadruple its 1995 GDP by the year 2010, but faces
challenges in environment protection as its economy grows.
</P>
<P>
Pollution prevention has been put high on the agenda. The
municipal government is to spend seven billion yuan on 82
environment projects by the end of the century and will increase
that input to account for more than one percent of the GDP after
the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"We have adopted policies to make sure that environmental
protection goes together with economic development, and that
pollution is brought under strict control by readjusting the
industrial structure, improving the energy structure, and
providing more facilities," the newly-elected Chongqing Mayor Pu
Haiqing says.
</P>
<P>
The city was raised to municipal status, which puts it directly
under the State Council, in March. It lies in a valley in Sichuan
province that is surrounded by hills. It had 0.34 mg of dioxide
sulphur per cu.m. of air in 1995, the second highest for China's
72 major cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
