<HEADLINE> Peru Sets Up El Nino Commission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori
today announced setting up of a national emergency commission to
cope with the case of an El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The commission, led by Minister of the Presidency Daniel
Hokama, will constist of ministers of agriculture, transport and
defense.
</P>
<P>
The commission will be responsible as dredging rivers,
consolidating bridges and repairing pumps, Fujimori said.
</P>
<P>
El Nino is a current that occurs in the southeastern Pacific
Ocean, which bring in tremendous rainfalls to the coastal areas of
Peru, causing floods and soil erosion.
</P>
<P>
Temperature along Peruvian seaside had risen recently with sea
surface temperature standing at two to three degrees Celsius
higher than normal.
</P>
<P>
Abnormality is also detected in air pressure and sea
wind. Floods have been forecast for the northern coast while
drought for southern mountainous areas.
</P>
<P>
The government is taking a series of measures against any
possible damage by El Nino to ensure that the disaster in 1982 and
1983 will not happen again, Fujimori said.
</P>
<P>
El Nino caused economic losses of 2 billion U.S. dollars to
Peru in the early 1980s. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
