<HEADLINE> Three S. African Countries Win Battle in Ivory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Botswana, Namibia and Zimbabwe
today won their battle to resume ivory trade by getting
permission for regulated trade in elephant products at the
Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species (CITES)
confernce to be concluded Friday.
</P>
<P>
Their proposals were approved as they met the required two-thirds majority.
</P>
<P>
The votes, casted by secret ballot on an individual basis, were
on the modified proposals by the three Southern African
countries.
</P>
<P>
The result for Botswana was 74 in favour, 21 against and 24
abstentions while 74 delegates voted in favour of Namibia's
proposals, with 22 voting against and 24 abstaining.
</P>
<P>
Host Zimbabwe received 77 votes in favour while 23 were against
the proposal and 20 abstained.
</P>
<P>
On June 17, the three countries lost their joint proposal on ivory
trade by only three votes short of majority.
</P>
<P>
According to three new individual proposals, the three countries
will be allowed to sell their ivory stocks exclusively to Japan after
observing an 18-month moratorium under strict conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
