<HEADLINE> China Approves British Candidate for Consul General in HK SAR </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Ministry Spokesman
Cui Tiankai announced here today that China has approved
Mr. Robert Francis Cornish to be the Consul General of Britain in
China's Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
At a routine press conference, Cui said that Sino-British joint
declaration has worked out rules in principle on the establishment
of consulate general of Britain in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese and British governments reached an agreement on
September 26, 1996 on Chinese government's approval for Britain to
set up a consulate general in the Hong Kong SAR, noted Cui.
</P>
<P>
On June 13 this year, the British Embassy in Beijing presented
a note to the Chinese Foreign Ministry saying that the Queen of
Britain had appointed Mr. Robert Francis Cornish to be the first
British Consul General in the Hong Kong SAR, added the Spokesman.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Vienna Convention on Consular Relations
and relevant Chinese regulations, said Cui, the Chinese Foreign
Ministry presented an answer note today to the British Embassy in
Beijing, approving Mr. Robert Francis Cornish to be the British
Consul General in the Hong Kong SAR and allowing him to perform
his consular duties within consular spheres starting July 1.
</P>
<P>
He noted that this afternoon, Councillor Ye Minglang of the
Consular Affairs Department of the Chinese Foreign Ministry
presented a consular certificate to Anthony D. Sprake, minister of
the British Embassy in Beijing on Chinese government's approval
for Mr. Robert Francis Cornish to perform consular duties in the
Hong Kong SAR.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
