<HEADLINE> Indo-Pak PMs Contact on Restored Hotline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The prime ministers of Pakistan
and India today held their first conversation on a restored
telephone hotline.
</P>
<P>
Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral contacted Pakistani
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on the hotline as a goodwill gesture
at the start of a new round of the foreign secretary-level talks
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to a press release issued here today by the Foreign
Office, Gujral wished the talks a success.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed his resolve to continue efforts for the
promotion of good-neighborly relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Sharif reiterated Pakistan's commitment to working for the
resolution of all outstanding issues, including the core issue of
Kashmir, between the two countries, the release said.
</P>
<P>
The decision to restore the hotline, which had remained dormant
soon after it was set up in 1989, was taken by the two prime
ministers at their meeting in Male, the Maldives, in May.
</P>
<P>
Indian Foreign Secretary Salman Haider will arrive here this
evening to begin tomorrow the new round of foreign secretary-level
talks with his Pakistani counterpart, Shamshad Ahmed, which is
scheduled to conclude on June 23.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that Pakistan will raise the reported deployment
of medium-range ballistic Prithvi missiles by India near its
border with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan has taken strong exception to the reported deployment
while India denies the report.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign secretaries are also expected to discuss the
possibility of forming working groups on all outstanding issues as
agreed upon by the prime ministers of the two countries at the
Male meeting. 
</P>
