<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreigners Account for 9 Percent of German Population </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The German Federal Statistics Office
said today that the number of foreigners living in the country has
increased to 7.3 million by the end of 1996, accounting for 8.9
percent of the total population of about 82 million.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics office based in Wiesbaden, the
latest foreigner figures represented a 1.6 percent increase from
the level of 1991 when there were about 5.9 million foreign
residents living in the country, or a share of 7.3 percent in the
whole population.
</P>
<P>
More than a fourth of the foreign population have lived in
Germany for 20 years or more but have not acquired German
citizenship. About half of the foreigners have lived in the
country for more than 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Among the foreign population, two million are Turks, followed
by 1.8 million migrating from other European Union countries, the
office said.
</P>
<P>
The increasing foreign population has aroused many debates
about Germany's current citizenship law, rooted in a 1913 imperial
decree that based nationality on German ancestry.
</P>
<P>
Many Germans have come to believe that the law is badly
outdated and there is an urgent need to integrate foreigners who
have settled in the country for dozens of years.
</P>
<P>
Until 1993, foreigners were obliged to wait 15 years and spend
thousands of dollars in fees to apply for German citizenship, and
there were no guarantees even after that.
</P>
<P>
Now an applicant must have only eight years' residency,
reasonable fluency in German and prove he can support a family
without state assistance. But there still remains daunting
obstacles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Election of SAR Chief Executive Marks a New Era in HK (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Election of the First Chief
Executive of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR)
is an event of historic significance in the history of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It marks the beginning of a new era when Hong Kong is governed
by Hong Kong people themselves.
</P>
<P>
According to the Basic Law of the HKSAR and relevant decisions
of the National People's Congress, the First Chief Executive
should be elected by a Selection Committee made up of 400 members
who are all permanent Hong Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
The Selection Committee is to be composed of 100 members from
each of the following four sectors: industrial, commercial and
financial sectors; the professions; labor, social services,
religious and other sectors; and former political figures, Hong
Kong deputies to the National People's Congress and
representatives of Hong Kong members of the National Committee of
the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC).
</P>
<P>
When specific methods for forming the Selection Committee had
been worked out, members of the Preparatory Committee (PC) for the
HKSAR each produced a namelist of recommended people from the
5,749 applicants who met qualification requirements. Then, at a
meeting, the Executive Council of the PC chose 409 candidates
strictly in accordance with the number of recommendations the
applicants had received from the PC members.
</P>
<P>
At its sixth plenary session held on November 2, 1996, the PC
elected 340 out of the 409 candidates as members of the Selection
Committee. Meanwhile, another 34 Selection Committee members were
chosen, through consultations, from among Hong Kong members of the
National Committee of the CPPCC. The 26 Hong Kong deputies to the
National People's Congress became Selection Committee members
automatically in accordance with methods of formation. The
400-member Selection Committee was thus formed.
</P>
<P>
While forming the Selection Committee, the PC accelerated the
pace of working out methods for electing the First Chief Executive
of the Hong Kong SAR.
</P>
<P>
The PC decided on qualification requirements for the first
Chief Executive of the Hong Kong SAR: he or she must be a Chinese
citizen of not less than 40 years of age who is a permanent
resident of the Region with no right of abode in any foreign
country and has ordinarily resided in Hong Kong for a continuous
period of not less than 20 years. And he or she must support the
Basic Law of the HKSAR and pledge allegiance to the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
The PC members agreed that the choice of candidates for the
first Chief Executive should be through election out of people
nominated on the basis of broad consultations in Hong Kong. A
namelist of nominated contenders would be distributed in Hong Kong
to invite opinions from all social strata.
</P>
<P>
After the method for selecting the Chief Executive was
announced, selection of the first Chief Executive entered an
operational stage.
</P>
<P>
According to relevant stipulations, applicants should first
express their intention to enter the race and fill in an
application form. Applicants would become contenders for candidacy
when the PC Executive Council determines that they meet
qualification requirements. The next step: those who obtain at
least 50 votes from members of the Selection Committee would
become formal candidates for the HKSAR Chief Executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
