<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks Hit New Record High After Weak Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Australian share market
staged a dramatic recovery to close at a new record, having fallen
sharply at the open on the back of another decline on Wall Street
overnight.
</P>
<P>
The broad-based improvement, which started gaining momentum
around mid-morning, was particularly evident in the banking and
building materials sectors and leading blue chips News Corp and
mining giant BHP Co.
</P>
<P>
The all ordinaries index ended 19.9 points firmer at a fresh
record of 2,693.3, off an intraday low of 2,660.4.
</P>
<P>
Brokers said overseas buying came into the market amid
suggestions at least one leading US institution had re-rated the
Australian market overnight.
</P>
<P>
"From what I can gather it was overseas buying that came into
our market due to an overnight re-rating by some of the leading US
institution positive towards the Australian market," one broker
said.
</P>
<P>
Reynolds &AMP; Co's Peter Struk said investors were chasing
high-yield, top quality stocks.
</P>
<P>
"The market was very strong," he said.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index finished 31.6 points firmer at
4,209.5, while the all resources rose 11 to 1,528.1.
</P>
<P>
BHP was one of the strongest performers of the leading stocks,
putting on 2.34 percent, or 45 cents, to end at 19.72 Australian
dollars, off an earlier low of 19.11 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Rio Tinto, another mining giant, fell 19 cents to 23.04
Australian dollars and WMC added 11 cents to 8.55 Australian
dollars.
</P>
<P>
News Corp helped the industrials higher, gaining 11 cents, or
1.79 percent, to 6.25 Australian dollars on turnover of 3.8
million shares.
</P>
<P>
The banking index closed 64.3 points firmer at 4,829.2, with
ANZ bank increasing 25 cents to 9.80 Australian dollars, NAB up 18
to 18.83 Australian dollars, Westpac rising 12 to 7.87 Australian
dollars and CBA stronger at 15.20 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Macquarie Bank put on another 2.63 percent on the back of
market endorsement of the bank's plan to launch a high-yield debt
trust to finance a power station and investors seeking higher
returns by swapping banks.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said there was no extraordinary news to explain the 29
cents rise to 11.30 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index finished 16.7 points, or 1.09 percent, lower at
1,511.8, with gold bullion dropping to 339.50 US dollars an ounce
in Sydney from 341.75 US dollars last.
</P>
<P>
National turnover totaled 420.42 million shares valued at
918.18 million Australian dollars (688.63 million US dollars) with
falling issues outnumbering rises by 611 to 549.  
</P>
</TEXT>
