<HEADLINE> Indo-Pak Hotline Restored </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 19 (Xinhua)-- A hotline between the prime
ministers of India and Pakistan was restored today when Indian
Prime Minister Inder Kumar Gujral spoke to his Pakistan
counterpart, Nawaz Sharif, official sources said here.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders spoke for about five to six minutes sending
positive signals as the two sides began their second round of
talks at the foreign secretary level in Islamabad today.
</P>
<P>
The first round of talks, stalled for over three years, was
resumed here at the end of March this year.
</P>
<P>
The hotline, first set up by the late Prime Minister Rajiv
Gandhi and former Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto, had remained
dormant since 1989.
</P>
<P>
The decision to revive the hotline was taken by Gujral and
Sharif when they met in Male, capital of the Maldives, during last
month's summit meeting of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC), which embraces Bangladesh, Bhutan, India, the
Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.  
