<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty Reduced in Sub-Saharan Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Sub-Saharan Africa has made
substantial progress in reducing poverty, shows as a report
from the United Nations Development Program (UNDP).
</P>
<P>
The UNDP 1997 report on human development cites increased
life expectancy and reduced infant mortality rate in some of the
areas in Sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
Life expenctancy has increased from 40 to 50 years between
1960 and 1994 while the infant mortality rate over the past three
decades decreased from 167 per 1,000 live births to 97, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
Under-five mortality rate per 1,000 live births has reduced
from 280 to 175 over the past two and half decades.
</P>
<P>
Adult illiterates have been reduced to 42 percent from 73
percent for the past twenty years.
</P>
<P>
Net primary school enrolment ratio has increased to 59 percent
from 25 percent and the secondary school enrolment ratio to 38
percent from 13 percent during the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Good Litchi Harvest for South Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Maoming, in Guangdong Province,
which is known for its fruit production, expects to see its litchi
harvest this year reach 149,000 tons, 49 percent more than last
year, local officials say.
</P>
<P>
The city has 40,000 hectares of litchi trees this year.
</P>
<P>
Deng Zhenquan, an official in charge of fruit production, says
that nearly 20 percent of the litchis picked have been shipped to
other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
Per capita income of farmers on a major litchi farm in Dianbai
County will increase by 6,000 yuan this year, because of the
harvest, he added.
