<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - Three State-Owned Enterprises to List on HK Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Three of China's state-owned
enterprises are expected to be listed on Hong Kong Stock Market
later this month or early next month.
</P>
<P>
According to Hang Seng Index (HSI) Services Limited, First
Tractor Company Limited, Beijing Yanhua Petrochemical Company
Limited and Jiangsu Expressway Company Limited will list on the
Stock Exchange of Hong Kong on June 24, June 26 and July 3
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The three companies will be included as constituent stocks of
the Hang Seng China Enterprises Index (HSCEI).
</P>
<P>
With the addition of these three companies, there will be 32
constituent stocks in the HSCEI. The inclusion is in line with
the objective of compiling the HSCEI, which is to track the
overall performance of all China enterprises listed in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index is managed and compiled
by HSI Services Limited, which also compiles the Hang Seng Index,
Hang Seng MidCap 50 Index, Hang Seng London Reference Index, Hang
Seng Asia Index and Hang Seng China-Affiliated Corporations Index.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Arrests 19 Labor Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A civil servants strike from Monday has
led to the arrest of 19 labor leaders in northern Nigeria's Kaduna
State.
</P>
<P>
Among those arrested by the police is Abdulkarim Ibrahim, Chairman
of the State Public Service Negotiation Council which leads the
strike.
</P>
<P>
Acting Chairman of the council, Jolly Naili told reporters on
Wednesday that the workers remained resolute and would continue to stay
at home until their leaders were released and their demands met.
</P>
<P>
The civil servants are demanding the payment of a 50 percent
increase in medical, transport and housing allowances promised by the
state government four years ago.
</P>
<P>
The state administrator, Hamed Ibrahim Ali, has
been summoned to Abuja for consultation over the strike, local media
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk - Hong Kong Public Archives Building Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A new home for Hong Kong's
public archives, the Hong Kong Public Records Building, was
officially opened here today.
</P>
<P>
The 11-story building is the first purpose-built archives ever
constructed in Hong Kong. It has been designed and fitted with a
full range of environmental control facilities to accord the right
levels of protection to the different formats of archival records
kept in its compartmentalized records repositories.
</P>
<P>
According to a spokesman for the Government Records Service, in
addition to spacious reading rooms that cater for visitors with
different needs and interests, there are lecturing and exhibition
facilities to help promote the public awareness and interest in
the local historical heritage, and an automated search-aid system
to help users look for, identity and order the records they wish
to peruse.
</P>
<P>
Built at a cost of 104.5 million HK dollars (13.48 million U.S.
dollars), the building fully meets all known standards and
specifications set for the permanent preservation of archival
materials.
</P>
<P>
It took just over two years for the building to go from the
drawing board to its physical completion.
</P>
<P>
The building will open to the public Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At Least 23 People Die in Heat wave in Pakistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, June 19 (Xinhua) -- At least 23 people have died in
Pakistan this week in a sizzling heat wave, local newspapers
reported here today.
</P>
<P>
In the cities of Multan, Sahiwal and Dera Ghazi Khan in Punjab
province, nine people died from sunstroke.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, high temperatures claimed another 14 lives in the
arid Thar area in the southern province of Sindh, the reports
said.
</P>
<P>
The heat wave hit many parts of Pakistan this week. High
temperatures ranging from 40 to 46 degree Celsius have severely
affected people's normal life in various parts of the country,
said the reports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 10:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are business briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey earned 6 billion U.S. dollars from its
tourism industry in 1996, according to latest figures announced by
the State Institute of Statistics (SIS).
</P>
<P>
The SIS said in a statement available today that a total of
7.97 million foreign tourists visited Turkey last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, 51.1 percent tourists are
holiday-makers.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The London-based HSBC Markets will run Jordan's first
corporate with 100 million U.S. dollars worth of Eurobonds issued
by the Jordan Phosphate Mines Company.
</P>
<P>
The English-language newspaper Jordan Times Wednesday quoted
John Pascoe, member of the HSBC group, and also chief executive
officer (CEO) of the Jordanian branch of the British-Mideast
Bank, as saying that "We will be arranging and underwriting the
deal."
</P>
<P>
HSBC Markets were chosen from seven bidders shortlisted for the
100 million dollars, by the Jordan Phosphate Mines Company under
the guidance of the Central Bank of Jordan and the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan will start a new round of negotiations with
the World Bank (WB) to secure a loan of 62 million U.S. dollars
for the improvement of tourism infrastructure in the kingdom,
local newspapers said today.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations with a WB team will start next Saturday in
Amman to get a 32 million dollars credit to finance tourism
projects in Petra, Wadi Rum and other tourist sites in Jordan,
said Jordanian Minister of Planning Rima Khalaf.
</P>
<P>
The total cost of these tourist projects amounted to 44
million dollars. The remaining 12 million dollars will be paid
by Jordan, Khalaf added.
</P>
<P>
Another part of the 62-million-dollar-loan will be used to
finance some of the social security network projects in Jordan,
the minister said.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Qatar will set up a bank for joint-venture
industries of medium and small scale in the country, a local
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
The bank, under the name of the Qatar Industrial Development
Bank, is partly owned by the state and the remainder by seven
other banks and private companies, the Gulf News said.
</P>
<P>
Its authorized capital is 54.94 million U.S. dollars,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The Qatar National Bank, 50 percent owned by the government
has 20 percent stake in the new bank, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey and Ukraine has signed an agreement for the
construction of a pipeline linking Turkey's Mediterranean port
city of Ceyhan and the Black Sea port of Samsun, according to the
semi-official Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The pipeline is designed to transport oil to Ukraine from
oil-rich Middle East countries, including Iraq, Iran and Saudi
Arabia, according to the accord signed here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources here said that it will take around two years
to complete the project which has an annual capacity of
transporting 25 million tonnes of oil. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Bourse Index Down 18.17 Points </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Stock Exchange of Thailand
(SET) index today declined 18.17 points from Wednesday to close at
464.77, as Thai deputy prime minister and finance minister Amnuay
Virawan resigned.
</P>
<P>
Some 176.45 million shares worth 5.916 billion baht (236.64
million U.S. dollars) changed hands today in a total of 43,931
transactions, with declining issues outnumbering advancing issues
262 to 69.
</P>
<P>
The SET index fell 14.78 points Wednesday from Tuesday to close
at 482.94 with some 141 million shares worth 3.739 billion baht
(149 million dollars) traded.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
