<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Leaves for Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
left here today for Paris to meet with his French counterpart
Jacques Chirac on their mediation efforts to rescue the Mideast
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The president was accompanied by a top-notch delegation,
including his political advisor Osama el-Baz. Foreign Minister
Amr Moussa, who has embarked on a three-nation European tour
since Wednesday, will join the delegation later today.
</P>
<P>
With the recent Mideast developments on the agenda of
Mubarak's visit, the two presidents will also discuss bilateral
ties and the outcome of the recent European Union summit.
</P>
<P>
In a statement adopted at the Amsterdam summit Wednesday, the
EU leaders urged Israel for the first time to consider allowing
the creation of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
The EU reaffirmed its opposition to Jewish settlements and
support for Arab-Israeli security cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Ambassador to France All Maher said Wednesday that
France stresses support for Egypt and for Mubarak's efforts
aimed at salvaging the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Europe has been seeking a stronger role in the Mideast
peacemaking and sent its special envoy to the region several
times in a bid to break the current crisis due to Israel's
construction of a new Jewish settlement in Arab East Jerusalem
three months ago.
</P>
<P>
Egypt managed to broker a meeting between Palestinian and
Israeli negotiators on June 8, but gap between the sides remained.
</P>
<P>
Moussa told reporters in Rome, Italy Wednesday that Egypt has
decided to temporarily put on hold the shuttle tours of Baz, its
envoy, between the Palestinian National Authority and Israel as
their crying rifts have rendered his mission futile.
</P>
<P>
The main obstacle to new substantive talks is the disagreement
over Israeli settlement activity, especially in Arab East
Jerusalem, where the Palestinians want to establish their future
capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Stock Index Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Composite Stock Index on the
Shanghai Stock Exchange finished at 1,230.74 today, down 1.94
points from the previous session, according to the China Finance
Trust and Investment Corporation.
</P>
<P>
The SSE-30 index, based on 30 blue chips that are selected from
more than 200 A shares for domestic investors on the Shanghai
Stock Exchange, closed at 3,837.09, up 18.86 points from the
previous session.
</P>
