<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ningxia's New Bridge on Yellow River Open to Traffic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The bridge across the Yellow
River in Zhongwei of northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous
Region opened for traffic Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The bridge has a length of 1,116 m and a width of 14 m. It was
built in 26 months at a cost of 74 million yuan. This is the
sixth bridge constructed in Ningxia, all of which cross the Yellow
River.
</P>
<P>
Yellow River, China's second longest, has a length of 397 km in
Ningxia.
</P>
<P>
The completion of the bridge has helped fulfil Ningxia's target
of replacing all previous ferryboat operations with national and
regional highways across the Yellow River with bridges erected by
the turn of this century.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia has 8,738 km of highways, including 7,900 km graded
ones. Yinchuan, the regional capital, has now been connected by a
highway network with 13 national and regional highways, and more
than 100 highways linking to different counties and township
seats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Standard &AMP; Poor's Optimistic About HK's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
Hong Kong, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Standard &AMP; Poor's has expressed
its optimism about Hong Kong's economic and credit strength after
its return to China.
</P>
<P>
A report released Wednesday by the well-known risk and credit
rating agency noted that "the closer union of a high-income,
international financial center with the world's emerging economic
giant has relatively little commercial downside.
</P>
<P>
Consistent with its optimism about the economic future of Hong
Kong and the rest of China, Standard &AMP; Poor's recently upgraded
the ratings of the Chinese mainland to triple-B-plus from
triple-B, and Hong Kong to single-A-plus from single-A.
</P>
<P>
The return of Hong Kong to China is accompanied by a good deal
of optimism about Hong Kong's continued economic success, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
This confidence is reflected in firm property values, a leap in
share prices on the stock exchange, and a surge in "sell-out" new
listings by mainland-related companies, it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
