<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cooperation With Hong Kong in Cleaning South China River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The border city of Shenzhen and
Hong Kong are cooperating in a large river-control project on the
37-km-long Shenzhen River, between the two cities, to clean it up
and make it more suitable for transportation.
</P>
<P>
On May 19, 1995, after 13 years of negotiations, local
governments began the first phase of a joint project on the
waterway which had caused environmental problems on both its banks
as it became narrower and dirtier day by day.
</P>
<P>
The first phase was completed a month ahead of schedule, and
the second phase started recently, while feasibility studies for
the third and fourth phases have been done.
</P>
<P>
The first phase treatment, which cost 279 million HK dollars,
has improved the river environment substantially.
</P>
<P>
When the project is completed in seven or eight years, the
river is expected to be widened to increase its flood-discharge
capacity to 2,100 cu.m. per second, from the present 600, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
By then, vessels of up to 500 tons will be able to use the
river, and it is likely to become another tourist site. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Concerned over Latest Situation in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN) today expressed concern over the latest
situation in Phnom Penh, Cambodia, hoping it will not jeopardize
Cambodia's entry into the regional grouping next month.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Abdullah Ahmad Badawi, who is
chairman of the ASEAN standing committee, said today at the
moment there was no threat to Cambodia's entry into the presently
seven-member grouping.
</P>
<P>
"I'm shocked by the report and will ask for accurate feedback
from the Malaysian ambassador to Cambodia. I prefer not to
speculate things and will wait for the report from Phnom Penh," he
told reporters after a social function here.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks while commenting on the
reportedly intense 90-minute gun battle between body-guard units
of Cambodia's co-prime ministers in Phnom Penh on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said he read a newspaper report today quoting a
Malaysian in Cambodia describing the situation there as not as bad
as the media had made it out to be.
</P>
<P>
"And now the situation is back to normal. I really want to know
what is happening and I will get our ambassador (in Cambodia)
Kamal Ismaun to submit a report," he said.
</P>
<P>
"The political situation in Cambodia is fluid by the hour, by
the day and anything can happen. There is no speculation in this
matter. We can only hope for the best," he said.
</P>
<P>
On whether there was a need for Malaysia, as ASEAN current
chairman, to be the mediator in mending the rift between Ranariddh
and the other co-premier Hun Sen, Abdullah said it was unnecessary
as it was "an internal problem".
</P>
<P>
During his separate meetings with Ranariddh and Hun Sen in
Phnom Penh 10 days ago, Abdullah said he had conveyed to them both
ASEAN's concern over the political situation in that country and
the co-premiers assured him that the "situation was improving"
and that cooperation between them was crucial to Cambodia's
future.
</P>
<P>
"I accepted what they told me and hoped nothing would happen."
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said ASEAN was hopeful for a peaceful Cambodia and
wanted Ranariddh and Hun Sen to continue working towards resolving
their differences.
</P>
<P>
During their one-day special meeting here last May 31, the
ASEAN foreign ministers agreed to admit Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar
into the regional grouping now comprising Brunei, Indonesia,
Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia, Laos and Myanmar are scheduled for admission into
ASEAN at the 30th ASEAN Ministerial Meeting here on July 24-25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
