<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Foreign Reserve Up Impressively by May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 17 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's foreign exchange reserve
shot up impressively to over seven billion U.S. dollars in May
from 5.9 billion dollars at the end of March, gaining 1.1 billion
dollars in two months.
</P>
<P>
The latest reserve position means Nigeria's rating in the
international economic community has improved since the country
has enough to pay for several more months of imports, local
newspaper This Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Finance Ministry sources as saying that the
position of the reserve should give some measure of confidence to
the opeators in the foreign exchange market as government now has
almost an elastic capacity to meet any level of demand for
foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the paper, a number of analysts contend
that the reserve are going up because the government is not
meeting its local and international financial commitments.
</P>
<P>
Higer forein currency reserves are believed to work in favor
of a country, especially as it helps keep its currency strong.
But the increase of reserve has not yet been helpful for curbing
the depreciation of the local currency due to the shortage of
foreign exchange supply. The market rate changed from one U.S.
dollar to about 80 Naira at the beginning of this year to present
87 Naira or so.
</P>
<P>
It is reported the Nigerian government, instead of using the
reserve to meet exchange demand, might have put substantial part
of the accumulated reserve to increase funding for upstream
(exploration) and downstream (refining) oil sector which are said
to be at the verge of collapse due to inadequate funding.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
