<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5,000 Former Zairean Refugees Register for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 19 (Xinhua) -- About 5,000 refugees from
former Zaire, now the Democratic Republic of the Congo, have
registered for voluntary repatriation after staying in Tanzania
for seven months, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The World Vision Communication Co-ordinator, Steven Kiruswa,
said in Arusha, Northern Tanzania on Wednesday that 4,000
refugees were from the Nyarugusu camp while 1,000 were from the
Lugufu camp. Both camps are in Kigoma Region, Western Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Kiruswa, who has just returned from a visit in Kigoma, said
that the refugees want to go back home after Laurent Kabila and
his allies successfully ousted Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko
in a seven-month civil war.
</P>
<P>
He said the refugees who registered themselves for voluntary
repatriation were among 100,000 Zaireans who fled their country
into Tanzania since the outbreak of the civil strife late last
October.
</P>
<P>
The number of refugees who wanted to go home is small because
the majority feared fresh fighting might erupt in the new Congo,
he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, more than 10,000 refugees from Burundi flocked into
Kigoma Region between May 15 and June 5 because of fresh fighting
in Burundi, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
