<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increasing Number of Highrises in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, June 19 (Xinhua)-- Although the 20th century is
an age of skyscrapers, China got off to a slow start, says Zhou
Bingzhang, an expert on highrise architecture, but it has built
8,000 buildings of more than 20 storys each since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Previously, high-rises could only be seen in Beijing and
Shanghai, the country's leading industrial and commercial center.
</P>
<P>
Construction work has picked up momentum since the late 1970s
because the country needed to accommodate its ever growing urban
population on a limited amount of space. Concrete with greater
strength, prestressed, and with steel reinforcing is now widely
used in China's highrises, bringing them closer to international
standards.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhou, highrises with steel structures are still
fairly new in China, with the shortest being a 14-storey mansion,
and the highest being the 88-story Pudong Financial Building in
Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Workers have completed 80 storeys of the building, which will
be China's tallest. The building will be 420 meters tall and will
be completed in August of 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NORAD, UNICEF Support Maternal Health Care in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Norwegian Agency for
Development Co-operation (NORAD) and the UNICEF Wednesday signed
1.2 million US Dollars agreement to support the effort to reduce
maternal deaths in Tanzania, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
NORAD and UNICEF will work for the reduction of maternal
mortality by 30 percent by the end of 1999 from the present
baseline of 770 per 100,000 live births.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a brief ceremony, Norwegian Ambassador to Tanzania
Nilsjohan Jorgensen said said Norway plans to spend 35 billion
Tanzania Shillings (about 58 million US Dollars) for various
social development programs in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF representive in Tanzania Agnes Aiidoo said maternal
death in the world, especially in developing countries including
Tanzania is alarming and called for concerted efforts to redress
the situation.
</P>
<P>
About 8,000 Tanzanian women die each year from
pregnancy-related diseases.
</P>
<P>
"This is an unacceptable situation. Women do not need to die
during pregnancy or chilld delivery," said Aidoo.
</P>
<P>
She said her organisation is committed to co-operation with
the governmental, non-governmental organisations and donors to
tackle the problem of maternal death.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, there are six million women of
chilld-bearing age and an estimated 1.2 million deliveries which
take place every year in the country.  
</P>
</TEXT>
