<HEADLINE> National Food Processing Policy Proposed in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Associated Chambers of
Commerce and Industry (ASSOCHAM), one of India's three main
industry associations, has proposed formulation of a national food
processing policy and unification of multi-pronged legislation
regulating manufactured food products.
</P>
<P>
In a paper drafted for discussion at a seminar on food
processing industry at Bangalore in southern India Thursday,
ASSOCHAM called for a two-pronged strategy to double India's share
in the international market by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The proposed policy laid emphasis on research and development,
better credit facilities through setting up of more branches of
banks and creation of a favorable investment climate. The paper
ranked food processing in India at fifth position in its
contribution to the manufacture of value-added products and first
in terms of employment accounting for 17 percent of the total
labor force.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the research and development strategy in
food processing industry should aim at improvement in the quality
of processed agricultural commodities and foods, development of
new uses and technology for agricultural products, and promotion
of integrated agro-industrialization.  
</P>
