<HEADLINE> Carved Screen For Hong Kong Hall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The "one country, two systems"
arrangement for Hongkong's return found a new embodiment as a
7-meter-long screen covered with gold, marble and relief
sculptures was erected in the hall of Hong Kong in the Great Hall
of the People in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The two totally different sides of the screen resembles the
capitalist system in Hong Kong and the socialist system in the
inland respectively.
</P>
<P>
According to its designers from the Beijing Arts and Crafts
Wood Carving Plant, the screen juxtaposes traditional Chinese
designs and western style white marble columns. The two sides fit
seamlessly with each other to form a piece that is unique in the
country's wood carving history, they said.
</P>
<P>
On one face side of the screen is embedded calligraphic words
by Chinese President Jiang Zemin. Each character of the
calligraphy is carved out of linden (soft) wood and covered with
goldleaf.
</P>
<P>
Next to each side of the calligraphy are relief wood
carvings. Among the designs are a mountain of bronze swords,
implying the supreme cause of the reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
On the back side of screen is a huge color ink painting
entitled "Lotus Pond with Widespread Fragrance." It depicts one
hundred lotus flowers to celebrate the return of Hong Kong. The
author of the painting is Yuan Yunpu, professor of the Central
Institute of Arts and Crafts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
