<HEADLINE> More Overseas People Fascinated by Traditional Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 19 (Xinhua) -- Overseas people, especially
those in Southeast Asia, have become so fascinated by traditional
Chinese medicine and acupuncture that an increasing number of them
have entered Chinese universities to study it.
</P>
<P>
The Traditional Chinese Medicine University of Guangzhou now
has 370 overseas students, three-fourths of whom come from
Southeast Asian countries, the United States and Europe as well as
Taiwan, Hong Kong and Macao. It has graduated more than 640
trainees from 76 countries and regions since it began to receive
enrolment applications from abroad in the 1970s. The university
also offers short-term training courses every year. More than
2,700 people from 45 countries and regions have received such
training.
</P>
<P>
"We have a group of teachers who can speak fluent English or
Japanese, making the learning much easier," said a head teacher at
the university.
</P>
<P>
The university has also sent nearly 200 professors and experts
to world-famous institutes and universities each year to deliver
speeches or conduct medical exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The university and the US's University of California have
jointly opened up a garden to grow medicinal herbs for scientific
research.
</P>
</TEXT>
