<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Offer Loans to Needy Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government is expected to
unroll a national education loan program to offer low-interest
loans to students from low-income families in a bid to encourage
them to receive education.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the Krung Thai Bank on behalf of the Finance
Ministry will lend 10.95 billion baht (438 million US dollars) to
some 300,000 students at an annual rate of one percent with a
repayment period of 15 years after they have been employed for two
years, local newspapers said today.
</P>
<P>
Eligible students must be enrolled at a high school or be
studying for a bachelor's degree and their parents' annual income
must below 300,000 baht (12,000 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
The program is part of the government's policy to promote
education in the country, which is undergoing economic slowdown in
recent years due to lack of skilled labor and professionals.
</P>
</TEXT>
