<HEADLINE> Italian FM Urges Resumption of Mideast Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Every effort must be made to "restart
the dialogue" between Israel and Palestinians in the stalled
Middle East peace process, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini
said today.
</P>
<P>
"Problems are easily hidden when the dialogue is interrupted,
and the principal concern now is to restart the dialogue even if
nobody knows the magic formula," Dini said at a meeting with
Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, who will continue his European trip to France and
Britain, praised the role Italy and the European Union have played
in the region.
</P>
<P>
Moussa's visit to Europe was considered important because it
came at the difficult time of continuous disorder in the Middle
East, especially in Hebron after the Israeli government decided to
build new housing in eastern Jerusalem for Jews.
</P>
<P>
He also acknowledged the contribution of the United States
despite concerns about the recent decision by the U.S. congress to
recognize Jerusalem as Israel's "indivisible capital," sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Both Egypt and Italy agreed that the stalled peace process
represents "a great risk for the region and for the people, and
demonstrates the need for initiatives, even from Europe to resume
the contacts between the two sides." 
</P>
