<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Has Bright Future, Says Trade Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will have a bright future
after China resumes the exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong on
July 1, Hong Kong's Permanent Representative to the World Trade
Organization (WTO) said here today.
</P>
<P>
Stuart Harbinson, in an interview with Xinhua, said:"Although
Hong Kong's return to China is only 12 days away, it is an event
for which there has been plenty of time for preparation because
the future of Hong Kong is very clearly set out in the blue book
(the Sino-British joint declaration signed in 1984).
</P>
<P>
"I do have great confidence in the future of Hong Kong. I
believe, owing to the strong quality of people in Hong Kong and
the sound legal framework for our future in terms of the basic
law, passed by China's National People's Congress after extensive
consultations with people in Hong Kong, that Hong Kong will have a
very bright future," Harbinson stressed.
</P>
<P>
Harbinson criticized the Western media for its biased reporting
of Hong Kong's return to China. "Unfortunately, the Western media
tends to concentrate too much on some of the negative aspects,"
said 49-year-old Harbinson, who is of British origin, but has
lived in Hong Kong since 1978.
</P>
<P>
"If anyone travels to Hong Kong today from the west, I think
that they just need to be there for about 10 minutes to realize
that life is normal in Hong Kong, and that people are behaving
normally, and that the great majority of them are confident of the
future."
</P>
<P>
He added: "It is very clear that for practical purposes on the
side of economy, the transfer has already taken place. Businessmen
are very confident about the future of Hong Kong and the economy
is doing extremely well.
</P>
<P>
"So I think everything is looking favorable for the future," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"In fact the return of Hong Kong to its motherland is in some
ways, from a commercial point of view, an improvement for the
future and provides new challenges and opportunities for our
businessmen."
</P>
<P>
In early June, Hong Kong notified members of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) that it would change its name to "Hong Kong,
China" from July 1.
</P>
<P>
Harbinson, Hong Kong's permanent representative to WTO since
September, 1994, said Hong Kong would continue to be a separate
customs territory, as set out in the 1984 Sino-British joint
declaration and the basic law passed by China's National People's
Congress after extensive consultations with people of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Explaining Hong Kong's future role in world trade, Harbinson
said: "We can continue to participate in relevant international
organizations such as WTO, using the name 'Hong Kong,
China'. We'll continue to do that and we'll continue to reflect
Hong Kong's own trade policies which are based on the promotion of
free trade and the strengthening of the multi-lateral trading
system."
</P>
<P>
Talking about China's accession to WTO, Harbinson said: "This
is very clearly in our own interest, and also in the interest of
the world trading system. It is in our interest because China is
our biggest trading partner. And therefore it is very important
that China should be part of the multi-lateral trading system."
</P>
<P>
Harbinson continued: "It is important for WTO itself because
the WTO cannot truly be a world organization or a global
organization unless it includes enormous countries like China. We
do hope very much that China will be able to join WTO as soon as
possible."
</P>
<P>
Harbinson hoped that the relationship between China and other
trade partners like the United States would be improved and
regulated by international rules. He believed that a trade dispute
between China and the U.S. would make Hong Kong suffer, and a more
stable relationship would be to the benefit of Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU to End Support for Short-Term Export Credit Insurance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission, the
European Union (EU)'s executive body, today adopted a
communication to its member states, aiming to end public support
for short-term export credit insurance.
</P>
<P>
The EC said in a press release that the primary purpose of the
communication was to remove distortions of competition due to
state aid to the export credit insurance. In the business there is
competition between public or publicly supported export credit
insurers and private export credit insurers.
</P>
<P>
The communication requests EU members to end, within one year
from its publication, the granting of state aid to public or
publicly supported export credit insurers in respect of export
credit insurance for which there is a commercial market.
</P>
<P>
However, in certain countries insurance cover for such export
credit risks may be temporarily unavailable on the commercial
market, the EU noted.
</P>
<P>
In such circumstances, these risks might, following
notification to the EC, be taken by public or publicly supported
export credit insurers operating for the account of or with the
guarantee of the state, the EC said.
</P>
<P>
Also existing complementary state reinsurance arrangements
remain permissible for an interim period, according to the press
release. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
