<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Land Commission Plays Big Role in Hong Kong's Smooth Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese side of the
Sino-British Land Commission has conscientiously performed the
duties as specified in Annex Three of the Sino-British Joint
Declaration and contributed to the smooth transition of Hong Kong
and its economic development ever since it was founded on May 27,
1985.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 13 years of land disposal, a total of 2,972
hectares of new plots were granted with the approval by the
Sino-British Land Commission, averaging 248 hectares annually. The
figure far exceeded the limits of 50 hectares as specified in
Annex Three of the Sino-British Joint Declaration for each year.
</P>
<P>
Proceeding from the actual needs from economic and social
development in Hong Kong, The Chinese side has granted rationally
and appropriately the amount of land supply each year in an effort
to facilitate the sustained economic growth in Hong Kong and the
improvement of living conditions of Hong Kong residents.
It has agreed to grant 60 ha of land to the Hong Kong Science and
Technology University for construction use, 33 ha for building an
industrial park at Tseung Kwan O, 67 ha for an inland dock at Tuen
Mun, 71 ha for the No. Nine Container Terminal and 1,248 ha for
building the Hong Kong new airport at Chek Lap Kok.
</P>
<P>
After careful planning and with the consent of the British
side, The Chinese Representative Office of the Sino-British Land
Commission in August 1986 announced the establishment of the Land
Fund of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) in a bid
to guarantee the economic interests of the future HKSAR Government
and the well-being of six million Hong Kong residents.
</P>
<P>
The Land Fund operates under the prerequisite of preserving the
principal sum and not affecting the monetary stability in Hong
Kong. It has made diversified investments on 14 leading financial
markets in the world with low risks but high returns.
</P>
<P>
In spite of a number of global or regional financial crises and
acute market competitions over the past 11 years, the Land Fund
has been very successful. The net value of its total assets was
only 772 million HK dollars when the fund was established and, on
July 1, the date when the Hong Kong SAR is founded, the trustees
of the Land Funds will turn over 170 billion HK dollars to the
Hong Kong SAR Government. And then the Land Fund will be managed
by the HKSAR Government.
The establishment of the Land Fund and its effective and smooth
operation is a vivid expression of the efforts of the Chinese
Government to protect the well-being of the six million Hong Kong
residents in the transitional period. It also give an eloquent
proof to the correctness for the decision of establishing the Land
Fund. And it is a good deed the central government has done for
the Hong Kong compatriots, and has won high praise from all social
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong SAR Government
spoke highly of the contributions made by the Land Fund to the SAR
Government and expressed his gratitude on behalf of his government
and the six million Hong Kong residents.  
</P>
