<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uruguayans Believe Mercosur Cut Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Most Uruguayans believe the
country's employment market suffered a decrease in jobs after the
establishment of the Southern Common Market (Mercosur), a report
in the "El Observador" newspaper said today.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted results of a recent poll organized by the
Associated Consulting Company. It said 55 percent of the
Montevideo residents and 37 percent of those living in other
Uruguayan provinces believed job opportunities had decreased in
the past six years.
</P>
<P>
Twenty percent of those questioned said job opportunities
remained the same while 18 percent said they increased.
</P>
<P>
In November 1991, Uruguay, together with Argentina, Brazil and
Paraguay, set up the Mercosur, the biggest regional bloc in South
America.
</P>
<P>
About 31 percent of those questioned in the poll said the
organization was of benefit to Uruguay, two percentage points less
than those who believed it was harmful.
</P>
<P>
Nineteen percent were neutral and 17 percent had no opinion.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen percent said they did not know whether the Mercosur
was operating, four percent believed that it was not and two
percent said they knew nothing about it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
