<HEADLINE> North Triangle Seeks Trade Agreement With Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from the
so-called North Triangle countries -- El Salvador, Guatemala and
Honduras -- met today in Guatemala to prepare for talks on forging
a free trade agreement with Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The talks will be held between the Central American delegations
and their Mexican counterpart in July when the free trade accord
is expected to be signed.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door meeting was attended by chief negotiators
Raul Trejo of Guatemala, Eduardo Ayala of El Salvador and Reynaldo
Osorio of Honduras.
</P>
<P>
Another 100 people, including economy and commerce ministry
officials, specialists and businessmen from the three countries
were seeking formulas for a common stand during the talks with
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
The participating countries divided their work into three areas
such as market access, technical standards, rules of origin and
tariff procedures.
</P>
<P>
Commercial standards, unfair trade practices, safeguard
measures, dispute settlement, services, investment, intellectual
property and government acquisitions were also reviewed.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is a follow-up of the meeting held last week in
San Salvador by the Mexican and North Triangle country
delegations which was of an negotiating nature. 
</P>
</TEXT>
