<HEADLINE> Russia, Ukraine to Cooperate in Fighting Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Letters of intention for cooperation
between the Russian and Ukrainian interior ministries in 1997-98
were initialed here today.
</P>
<P>
It followed talks between Russian Deputy Prime minister and
Minister of the Interior Anatoly Sergeyevich Kulikov, and
Ukrainian Minister of the Interior Yury Kravchenko.
</P>
<P>
In the talks, the ministers expressed the common view that the
two countries should strengthen cooperation between the ministries
in fighting crime, to safeguard the interests of both countries.
</P>
<P>
The Russian deputy prime minister said the situations in
fighting crime in Russia and Ukraine were similar. Therefore,
there was need for the countries' interior ministries to
coordinate their actions, and cooperate more closely. The two
countries should exchange data and information and keep constant
liaison and exchanges, especially in fighting organized crime,
drugs smuggling, illegal gun-trafficking and illegal immigration
on the borders, he said.
</P>
<P>
There were no contradictions between the two ministries, which
could impede bilateral cooperation, the Ukrainian minister stated.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian President Leonid Danilovich Kuchima also met the
Russian delegation today headed by Kulikov. 
</P>
