<HEADLINE> Expert Urges Stiffer Sentences for AIDS Offences </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- AIDS sufferers who intentionally
infect others with the virus should be jailed for the maximum
limit of 25 years, a Costa Rican official said today.
</P>
<P>
The President of College of Physicians Marco Antonio Batalla
was giving evidence before a congressional committee working on a
new bill on the prevention, treatment and study of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
He said that provisions in the bill regarding punishment for
intentionally infecting people with the AIDS virus were too
lenient and should be increased to the country's maximum permitted
jail sentence of 25 years.
</P>
<P>
The bill proposes that those who donate blood, semen, breast
milk, tissues or organs when they know they are infected should be
punished with a three to eight-year jail sentence.
</P>
<P>
HIV carriers who maintain sexual relations with others without
telling them they are infected should face a similar sentence, the
bill proposes.
</P>
<P>
Batalla also recommended that funds set aside for AIDS should be
used on prevention and not treatment of sufferers, as the
medication is expensive and doesn't cure the disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
