<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former British Ambassador Confident of Hong Kong's Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Former British Ambassador to China
Sir Robin McLaren said today he was confident that Hong Kong would
remain stable and prosperous after China resumes the exercise of
sovereignty over the region on July 1.
</P>
<P>
"I have great confidence in the people who were selected and
appointed to run Hong Kong and I know most of these people very
well," McLaren told Xinhua in an exclusive interview.
</P>
<P>
He said the transfer of power was very carefully prepared and
he had no doubt Hong Kong "will continue to be successful in the
coming years."
</P>
<P>
McLaren, 63, has been involved in Hong Kong affairs and in
Britain's relations with China for more than 35 years. He was
Political Adviser to the Hong Kong government from 1981 to 1985
and Senior Representative on the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group
from 1987 to 1989. Two years later, he was promoted as British
ambassador to China until 1994.
</P>
<P>
He said he believes Hong Kong will have a bright future
"because all the elements that have enabled it to enjoy such
spectacular success in the past are there and guaranteed in the
Joint Declaration."
</P>
<P>
"It is in everyone's interest that Hong Kong should succeed in the
future and in no one's interest it should not. It is in China's
interest, in the international community's interest and above all it
is in the interests of the people of Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
He said both Britain and China are handling the handover
well. "Confidence is high, the economy is in good shape, the
financial reserves are very strong indeed," so everything points
to a bright future in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The veteran diplomat said that although there were disputes
between Britain and China on Hong Kong affairs in the past, he
believes there should be no such problems in the future.
</P>
<P>
"In the past, because of British responsibilities toward Hong Kong
and because of different approaches to Hong Kong, there have been
some disputes and I think that is natural and perhaps
unavoidable."
</P>
<P>
But provided the Joint Declaration and Basic Law remain the
guiding text for Hong Kong and are honored by everybody concerned,
then there won't be problems on that issue. "I am sure the
relationship between Britain and China will flourish as never
before," he said confidently.
</P>
<P>
He predicted that Britain and China will cooperate well in Hong
Kong affairs in the future since the two countries share the same
interest -- to maintain a continued success in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
On Sino-British relations after the handover on July 1,
McLaren said the British government "wants to pursue positive
and constructive relations" with China.
</P>
<P>
"The new Labor government, like the Conservative government,
will seek to support business in Hong Kong as well as in
China... We want to see contacts increasing in every area and we
want to see mutually beneficial trade increase. We also want Hong
Hong to play a positive part in that process," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that after June 30, Hong Kong's role in bilateral
relations will change. In the past, Hong Kong has been a major
element in Sino-British relations and no other Western government
has had this kind of factor in its relations with China.
</P>
<P>
"At midnight on the 30th of June, Britain will cease to be
responsible for Hong Kong, no longer have those
responsibilities. Of course we will continue to preserve an
interest under the Joint Declaration," the former ambassador said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Hong Kong had played a very important role
in the modernization of China. He believed that role has not
finished yet and it will continue to play a huge and important
role after the handover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
