<HEADLINE> Colombia Adopts New Technology for Coffee Processing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- More than 3,000 coffee
plants in Colombia have adopted a new processing technology which
would reduce water consumption and pollution, Colombia's National
Coffee Research Center (Cenicafe) said today.
</P>
<P>
With this new method, known as Ecological Coffee Processing,
the water consumption in processing one kilogram of coffee was
reduced from 40 to 0.67 liters, Cenicafe Director Gabriel Cadena
said.
</P>
<P>
The reduction was achieved by recycling water, and the new
method also helped improve the quality of coffee, Cadena said.
</P>
<P>
Colombia's National Federation of Coffee Growers has promised
to provide subsidies of up to 50 percent of the investment needed
for processors to acquire the new technology. 
</P>
</TEXT>
