<HEADLINE> Pakistan Foreign Minister Visits Kazakhstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Foreign Minister Gohar
Ayub Khan and his Kazak counterpart Kasymzhomart Tokayev met here
today to discuss the Afghan situation and ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers believed it is of great importance
for the two countries to further develop their relations although
they have different views on how to solve the Afghan conflict, the
Kazakhstan Telegraph Agency (Kaz TGA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Gohar Ayub Khan, who arrived here earlier today on a two-day
visit, told the news agency at the airport that his trip is to
expound Pakistan's stand on the Afghan issue, open dialogue with
Afghanistan's neighboring countries and promote the earlier
realization of peace in that country.
</P>
<P>
He said he would also exchange views on the situation in
Central Asia with the Kazak side.
</P>
<P>
Tokayev said that Kazakhstan advocates that the conflicting
parties in Afghanistan should cease fire immediately and start
peace talks.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks should be held with the mediation of the United
Nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Gohar Ayub Khan will leave for Uzbekistan and Tajikistan after
talks with Kazak Prime Minister Akezhan Kazhegeldin Thursday.
</P>
