<HEADLINE> Ukraine to Change Non-alignment Stand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine could change its stand as a
non-aligned nation and may join a military organization or a
military political union, a senior government official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Vladimir Gorbulin, Secretary of the Ukrainian State Committee
on Security and Defense, told reporters "the door remains open for
Ukraine to join a military organization or a military political
union, which conforms to Ukraine's constitution."
</P>
<P>
He said Ukraine's friendship treaty with Russia, signed on May
31, would not block the way for the country to join such a body.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma and his Russian counterpart
Boris Yeltsin signed a friendship treaty to shape long-term
economic and political cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Russia strongly opposes the eastward expansion plans of the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) to take in countries of
the former Warsaw Pact.
</P>
<P>
In the past, Ukraine has highlighted its status as a
non-aligned country and said it would not join the western
military alliance, but only establish a special partnership with
it.
</P>
<P>
Gorbulin said Ukraine had held talks with the United States and
NATO after signing an accord with Russia on the division of the
former Soviet Union Black Sea Fleet at the end of May. They agreed
that the accord had not added any extraordinary responsibilities
or obligations on Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
"Ukraine maintains its right to act freely," the secretary said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Ukraine and Russia are still negotiating on
some small differences over the division of the Fleet, an issue
concerning the establishment of special partnership relations with
the NATO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0294 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Ushers In New Tide of Kong Kong Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The Shenzhen Special Economic
Zone is experiencing a new tide of Hong Kong investment, with big
financial groups from Hong Kong as the main players.
</P>
<P>
This indicates the full confidence of Hong Kong businesses in
the bright prospects for the economic cooperation between Hong
Kong and Shenzhen after the return of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In the first five months of this year, the city utilized 1.14
billion US dollars of overseas investment, a 57.6 percent
year-on-year rise. Of that sum, about 70 percent came from Hong
Kong, a local government official said.
</P>
<P>
Investment from Hong Kong financial groups are focusing on the
city's infrastructure, real estate and high-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
Several Hong Kong financial groups have decided to spend six
billion yuan (about 720 million US dollars) building residential
buildings in the new city area of Shenzhen. They believe that,
being a city next to Hong Kong, Shenzhen has great potential in
its real estate development.
</P>
<P>
The designed sea-bridge linking Shenzhen's Shekou development
zone with Hong Kong's Yuen Long is also attractive to Hong Kong
businessmen. Board chairmen of two financial groups have recently
visited Shenzhen, showing their interest in the project.
</P>
<P>
In Dapeng Bay, Li Ka Shing's corporation is engaged in the
second-phase construction of the Yantian Port, which is designed
to become the most important international transit port in
southern China.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, a feasibility study has been made for the
building of a science and technology park by Shenzhen and Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen has also begun to train software developers for Hong
Kong factories and companies.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that Hong Kong investment in Shenzhen totaled
7.63 billion dollars from 1979 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
Tang Ying-yen, Chairman of the Federation of Hong Kong
Industries, said in Shenzhen recently that Shenzhen has become a
necessary production base and support center for Hong Kong's
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
