<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Wetlands Home To Pere David's Deer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, June 19 (Xinhua) -- David's deer have been multiplying
in a nature reserve on the middle reaches of China's longest river.
</P>
<P>
This year, 30 head of deer have been born in a wetland area at
Shishou City in the Yangtze River Valley in Central China's Hubei
Province, bringing the total number of such deer to 138 in the
nature reserve established three years ago.
</P>
<P>
David's deer has the antlers of a deer, the head of a horse,
and the body of a cow. It was native to China until the early
years of the 20th century, when western imperialists invaded China
and took the remaining deer away from an imperial park.
</P>
<P>
David's deer came back to China when the Marquess of Tavistock
of England sent 20 of the rare animals to Beijing in 1985, thanks
to cooperation between the Chinese and British governments.
</P>
<P>
Pere David was a French Catholic priest and a naturalist who
first made a record of the unique deer in China in 1865.
</P>
<P>
The deer is now being raised in Beijing, and in Jiangsu and
Hainan provinces as well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
