<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> hkhk -Indian Businessmen, Believers of "One Country, Two Systems" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, June 19 (Xinhua) -- "During the past dozen years of
Hong Kong's transitional period, no member of the Indian business
community in Hong Kong has left because we're firm believers of
'one country, two systems'," said Raj Sital, chairman of the
Indian Chamber of Commerce in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Sital, who is 36 and in the second
consecutive term as the chairman, claimed that he and his fellow
businessmen have full confidence in the future of Hong Kong after
its return to China on July 1.
</P>
<P>
"I was born and raised in Hong Kong, and there are a lot of
people like me in our community. For us, Hong Kong is our home,"
said Sital, who speaks fluent Cantonese and a little Mandarin.
</P>
<P>
With a history of over 150 years, the Indian community in Hong
Kong now has more than 25,000 people. Indian business people run
nearly 1,000 companies in Hong Kong, which are mostly engaged in
import and export trade.
</P>
<P>
"Each year we handle some 8 percent of Hong Kong's total
foreign trade volume," said Sital proudly.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Indian Chamber of Commerce, which was founded in
1952 and now has approximately 500 members, is one of the oldest
foreign chambers of commerce here.
</P>
<P>
Sital noted that the majority of the business for Indian
merchants in Hong Kong has involved the re-export of goods
produced in the interior area of China.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking forward to Hong Kong's return to China, for we
believe that our business with the Chinese interior area will
become more smooth and can be done better after that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that trade between Hong Kong and India has been
growing steadily over the past decade. In 1996, the volume of
trade between India and Hong Kong surpassed 21.1 billion Hong Kong
dollars (about 2.7 billion U.S. dollars), and India became the
15th largest supplier and 28th largest market for Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sital said, the total volume of trade between India
and China last year reached 1.406 billion U.S. dollars, up 20.9
percent over 1995.
</P>
<P>
"India has become China's largest trade partner in South Asia
for two years in succession," he noted.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out that there is still a lot of room for
development in the Sino-Indian trade, for both China and India are
"very large countries with a lot to offer".
</P>
<P>
"A lot of goods produced in China and India are complementary
to each other, such as light industrial products of China and
pharmaceuticals and raw materials of India," he added.
</P>
<P>
Being the gateway to China, he said, Hong Kong will play a very
important role in promoting the trade relationship between India
and China.
</P>
<P>
"Many members of our chamber have set up businesses in China,
and I believe that this trend will continue," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
