<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Lifts Foschi Suspension </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAUSANNE, June 18 (Xinhua) -- American swimmer Jessica Foschi
had her two-year suspension for steroid use cut by the Court of
Arbitration for Sport (CAS) on Wednesday, clearing the way for her
immediate return to international competitions.
</P>
<P>
FINA, international swimming's governing body, who had banned
Foschi after she tested positive for the metabolic steroid
nesteroton at the 1995 U.S. national championships and who later
turned down an appeal, were ordered to pay the American teenager
15,000 Swiss francs to cover her court costs.
</P>
<P>
The CAS reduced the suspension from two years to six months,
from August 4 1995 to February 3 1996.
</P>
<P>
The ruling ends a rollercoaster saga of bans and appeals that
stretches back to August 4 1995 when the then 15-year-old American
first tested positive.
</P>
<P>
Foschi was originally placed on two years' probation last June
by the U.S. Swimming National Board of Review but a subsequent
appeal to the American Arbitration Association reversed all
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
Under growing pressure to clean up the sport, FINA took up the
case and conducted their own investigation suspending the swimmer
for two years on August 3 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
