<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East China Province Prepares Against Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, June 19 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang Province
has conducted more than a week of rescue drills to get ready for
the flood season, which is drawing near.
</P>
<P>
This is just one part of the coastal province's annual measures
against floods. Last year, the province and much of the rest of
South China suffered losses measured at 220 billion yuan due to
floods caused by typhoon.
</P>
<P>
The province has set up flood-control headquarters in various
government offices, and has the local army ready to add thousands
of troups to join in the flood control efforts.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang is hit by rainstorms, windstorms and typhoons every
year. It plans to have all dykes, dams and reservoirs repaired
before the flood season sets in in July.
</P>
<P>
The province's measures are being met with enthusiastic support
by local people. Ningbo, Wenzhou, Taizhou and other cities are
building sea dykes according to high standards. Wenzhou, which was
badly hit by typhoons in recent years, has built a 19-km long dyke
that could withstand the worst floods in 50 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Chinese Sturgeon Found In Bohai Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 19 (Xinhua) -- An 82-cm-long Chinese sturgeon has
been found in north China's Bohai Bay, according to "China
Environmental News".
</P>
<P>
The rare fish, weighing about three kg., was caught earlier
this month by Zhu Shaobo, a fisherman, who set it free three days
later.
</P>
<P>
This was the second Chinese sturgeon found in Bohai Bay. The
first one, weighing 200 kilograms, was found there in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese sturgeon, known as a "living fossil", is thought to
have been in existence in the Yangtze River for more than 140
million years. The fish has top state protection in China.
</P>
<P>
Why the fish has found itself in Bohai Bay remains a mystery,
according to experts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
