<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Province Intensifies Protection of Farmland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, June 19 (Xinhua) -- South China's Guangdong province
has succeeded in checking the reduction of farmland, thanks to its
package of effective measures.
</P>
<P>
The amount of land used for non-agricultural purposes was
14,000 hectares in 1996, a quarter less than in the previous
year. The amount of farmland used for such purposes was 6,100
hectares, more than 20 percent less than in the previous year. At
the same time, the province reclaimed an additional 12,000
hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
The real estate development and development zone fever at the
beginning of the 1990s caused a big reduction of farmland in the
province and many people abandoned their land to take up
businesses, causing a large amount of farmland to lie idle.
</P>
<P>
To arrest the trend, the provincial government issued 13 sets
of regulations and over 20 administrative decrees on land
administration and protection. In 1994, the province designated 2
million hectares of basic farmland for priority protection that
are not allowed to be used for purposes other than farming. In
addition, the province has appropriated a large sum of money for
restoring the farmland that has been lying idle. Last year, the
province decided not to supply land for building high grade
buildings and golf courses.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to these measures, grain production of the province has
increased for three consecutive years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian, South African Nickel Giants Merged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- A 1.72 billion US dollar nickel
mining and refining giant was created in Australia Wednesday with
the announcement of a merger of South African minerals
conglomerate Gencor's nickel assets with Australia's dominant
refiner, Queensland Nickel.
</P>
<P>
The merged group will account for more than seven percent of
the international production and will be one of the four biggest
nickel producers in the world, the Australian Financial Review
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The group will also account for about eight percent of the
world cobalt production.
</P>
<P>
The merger coincides with some good news for nickel price, with
the Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics
predicting this week that world nickel consumption may exceed
production for the first time in several years.
</P>
<P>
If the deal is approved by shareholders and regulators, control
of Queensland Nickel (QNI) will effectively pass to Gencor, which
will end up with 55 percent of the merged company.
</P>
<P>
The merged group will remain headquartered in Australia under
the banner of QNI, a refiner producing nickel metal from ore
imported from New Caledonia, Indonesia and the Philippines.
</P>
<P>
After the merger, which is expected to be completed by
mid-August, the group will have refining and production assets
spanning South America, Australia and Southeast Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
