<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Researcher Views Hong Kong's Credit as Stable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 18 (Xinhua) -- China has powerful economic
incentives to respect the autonomy underpinning Hong Kong's credit
stability, the Standard &AMP; Poor's, a famous rating company of the
U.S., said here in a series of reports today.
</P>
<P>
The reports evaluated the impact Hong Kong's transfer of power
will have on sovereign, financial institution, structured finance,
and real estate credit quality.
</P>
<P>
One of the reports said that the transfer of sovereignty is
accompanied by a good deal of optimism about Hong Kong's continued
economic success. This confidence is reflected in firm property
values, a leap in share prices on the stock exchange, and a surge
in "sell-out" new listings by mainland-related companies.
</P>
<P>
In May, Standard &AMP; Poor's raised its rating on Hong Kong one
notch to single 'A'-plus.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong'continued prosperity is also a key to the success of
China's "one country, two systems" policy, said the Standard &AMP;
Poor's director Lacey Gallagher. "Hong Kong is the model for the
system that China hopes to eventually put in place in Taiwan,
whose recovery is one of China's important, long-term policy
goals," she added.
</P>
<P>
She also said that Hong Kong has had a very stable and
conservative set of financial policies for decades, which might
help stablize the region's financial system.
</P>
<P>
One of its reports said that demand for property, particularly
residential property, in Hong Kong will continue to be very strong
relative to supply after the transfer of sovereignty. The local
property prices will be kept high relative to global standards.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong banks are sensitive to the property sector's
performance due to their loan portfolios' exposure to real estate.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that the health of the property sector
has an enormous impact on Hong Kong's economy particularly the
corporate, bank and government sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
