<HEADLINE> Major News Items In Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, June 19 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian news papers today:
</P>
<P>
The Australian
</P>
<P>
-- The government threatened yesterday to dump the
Constitutional Convention or scrap voters' rights to elect its
members after the Senate rejected the Coalition's plans for
deciding on a republic.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald
</P>
<P>
-- The federal government's plans for a Constitutional
Convention on the republic were thrown into disarray yesterday
when the Senate insisted on a full compulsory ballot to elect half
of the delegates.
</P>
<P>
The Age
</P>
<P>
-- Industrial strife in Victoria's public hospitals worsened
yesterday with a campaign by non-medical staff spreading to 35
hospitals. More than 400 beds stayed closed as the nurses' dispute
dragged on.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review
</P>
<P>
-- Japan is turning its back on Australia as a place to invest
while its investments across the rest of the world are booming.
New figures show that Japanese foreign direct investment in
Australia slumped to 750 million US dollars in the 12 months to
March 1997, its lowest level in a decade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
