<HEADLINE> U.S. Dollar Ends Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 18 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. dollar recouped from a
drop caused by a surging Japanese trade surplus to end higher
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The dollar fell to an intraday low of 112.90 yen in early
dealings before recovering to settle in New York at 113.65 yen, up
from 113.31 Tuesday. The dollar settled at 1.7333 marks, up from
1.7308. The pound remained unchanged at 1.6388 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Japan's finance ministry reported overnight that the Japanese
trade surplus in May totaled 738.27 billion yen, tripling the
level of a year earlier. The surplus with the United States nearly
doubled to 322.87 billion yen, the eighth consecutive monthly
increase.
</P>
<P>
But U.S. officials' reaction to the data was viewed in the
foreign-exchange market as tame, which helped the dollar
strengthen.
</P>
<P>
Against European currencies, the dollar's strength reflected
further indications that the European Union will have to loosen
the strict criteria on deficit reduction designed to keep the euro
strong when it debuts in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
Other late-dollar rates in New York compared with late Tuesday:
1.4478 Swiss francs, up from 1.4447; 5.8490 French francs, up from
5.8365; 1,696.25 Italian lire, up from 1,693.75; 1.3923 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.3864.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
