<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bundesbank: Upturn in German Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Germany's economy now is out of
stagnation and on the upswing, said the Bundesbank in a monthly
report released today, noting a seasonally-adjusted 2.75 percent
growth in the first quarter over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The economic upturn occurred despite continued depressed
domestic market and high unemployment.
</P>
<P>
In its report for June, the central bank also pointed out that
German industry had resumed its competitiveness on the
international market.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bundesbank, strong exports remained the most
important factor to boost economy. Foreign orders rose by 12
percent in the first four months this year compared to a year
earlier, it added.
</P>
<P>
The report blamed the strong exports on rationalization
measures, a favorable agreed wage increase of around 1.5 percent
and the lower German Mark rate, which so "largely corresponds to
economic fundamentals."
</P>
<P>
Mark's value against the world's other 18 key currencies now is
lower than at the start of 1995, it is reported.
</P>
<P>
The Bundesbank also urged in the report quick political
decisions on reforms in order to improve the framework conditions
for corporate investments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
