<DOCNO> XIE19970619.0327 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-06-19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Stocks Move Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, June 18 (Xinhua) -- Technology stocks led a second
day of declines on Wall Street today as investors backed off the
record-breaking gains of the past two weeks.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the decline, following a drop in Tuesday's Dow,
marked the predictable end of a record-breaking streak that raised
the blue chip index more than 300 points in less than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones Industrial average closed down 42.07 points to
7,718.71.
</P>
<P>
Decliners narrowly outnumbered advancers on the New York Stock
Exchange, where volume totaled 491.68 million shares as against
542.97 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 list fell 5.72 to close at 888.71,
snapping an eight-session streak of record highs. The NYSE
composite index was down 1.68 to 463.41. The Nasdaq composite
index fell 10.60 to 1,432.51, ending three consecutive sessions of
record-breaking closes.
</P>
<P>
But the American Stock Exchange composite index edged up 0.11
to 625.97.
</P>
<P>
The share price of computer hard disk-drive maker Seagate
Technology led the decline, which carried over to tech stocks like
chip maker Intel and software giant Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the market is already convinced that the Federal
Reserve will not raise interest rates when it meets July 1-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
