<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Calls for Immediate End to Israeli-Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 18 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan today called for an immediate end to Israel-Palestinian
clashes in Hebron, said a statement by the spokesman's office.
</P>
<P>
Scores of Palestinians have been shot and wounded by Israeli
troops in the West Bank town of Hebron during the past four days
of violent protests.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General is following with concern recent
developments in Hebron and calls for an immediate end to the
violence and appeals for maximum restraints," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
"The tragic events of the past few days underline the urgent
needs for confidence to be restored, for all sides to restrain
from provocative acts and for conditions to be created in which
the Peace Process can be resumed," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Israel-Palestinian peace talks have been deadlocked since the
Israeli Government decided in March to go ahead with a Jewish
settlement in Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians say the settlement breaks international law
and preempts the talks on the final status of Jerusalem and the
Palestinian territories. Israel refuses to stop building
settlements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
